{"title_page": "Gina Raimondo", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{short description|75th Governor of Rhode Island}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Gina Raimondo this is all fake\n|image        = Governor Gina Raimondo of Rhode Island.jpg\n|order        = 75th [[Governor of Rhode Island]]\n|lieutenant   = [[Daniel McKee]]\n|term_start   = January 6, 2015\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Lincoln Chafee]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = Chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]]\n|term_start1  = December 1, 2018\n|term_end1    = December 4, 2019\n|predecessor1 = [[Jay Inslee]]\n|successor1   = [[Phil Murphy]]\n|office2      = General Treasurer of Rhode Island\n|governor2    = Lincoln Chafee\n|term_start2  = January 4, 2011\n|term_end2    = January 6, 2015\n|predecessor2 = [[Frank T. Caprio|Frank Caprio]]\n|successor2   = [[Seth Magaziner]]\n|birth_name   = Gina Marie Raimondo\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1971|5|17}}\n|birth_place  = [[Smithfield, Rhode Island]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Andrew Moffit|2001}}\n|children     = 2\n|education    = [[La Salle Academy, Providence|LaSalle Academy]]<br>[[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|AB]])<br>[[New College, Oxford]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|DPhil]])<br>[[Yale University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]]) \n}}\n'''Gina Marie Raimondo''' ({{IPAc-en|r|\u0259|\u02c8|m|\u0252|n|d|o\u028a}}; born May 17, 1971) is an American politician and venture capitalist serving, since 2015, as the [[Governor of Rhode Island|75th]] [[Governor of Rhode Island]]. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], she is the first woman to serve as Governor of Rhode Island.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/democrat-gina-raimondo-wins-rhode-island-governor-race-032616738.html;_ylt=AwrBTzkMVFpU7mAAlqZx.9w4|title=Democrat Gina Raimondo becomes Rhode Island's first female governor|date=November 5, 2014|work=Yahoo News|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Prior to her election, she served as General Treasurer of [[Rhode Island]] from 2011 to 2015 and was the second woman to hold the office. She was selected as the Democratic candidate for Rhode Island's governorship in the [[2014 Rhode Island gubernatorial election|2014 election]]. Raimondo won the election on November 4, 2014, with 41% of the vote, in a three-way race, against the Mayor of [[Cranston, Rhode Island|Cranston]], Republican [[Allan Fung]], and businessman [[Robert J. Healey|Robert Healey]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sullivan|first1=Sean|title=Raimondo launches campaign for Rhode Island governor|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2013/12/18/raimondo-launches-campaign-for-rhode-island-governor/|work=The Washington Post|date=December 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nRaimondo was elected to serve as the Vice Chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]] for the [[2018 United States gubernatorial elections|2018 election cycle]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20171204/raimondo-to-help-lead-democratic-governors-group|title=Raimondo to help lead Democratic Governors group|last=Gregg|first=Katherine|work=providencejournal.com|access-date=2017-12-05|language=en}}</ref> She was the Chair of the Democratic Governors Association, and was only the second woman to serve in that position.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20181201/ris-raimondo-elected-to-lead-democratic-governors---audio|title=R.I.'s Raimondo elected to lead Democratic governors {{!}} audio|last=Gregg|first=Katherine|website=providencejournal.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref> Raimondo ran for and won reelection to a second term in [[2018 Rhode Island gubernatorial election|2018]], and becoming the first candidate to secure a majority of votes for that office since [[2006 Rhode Island gubernatorial election|2006]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nGina Marie Raimondo was born May 17, 1971<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ballotpedia.org/Gina_Raimondo|title=Gina Raimondo|publisher=ballotpedia.org|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> in [[Smithfield, Rhode Island]], where she later grew up. Of Italian descent, she is the youngest of Josephine (Piro) and Joseph Raimondo's three children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://funeralhomeweb.net/default.aspx?MemberId=134509&FLVId=|title=Nardolillo Funeral Home Published an Obituary for Joseph  Raimondo|work=Nardolillo Funeral Home Website|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ginaraimondo.com/about|title=About Gina|work=Gina Raimondo for RI|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Her father worked for a watch company. Raimondo graduated from [[La Salle Academy, Providence|LaSalle Academy]], in Providence, as one of the first girls<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/breaking-news/content/20141002-la-salle-academy-removes-all-photos-from-wall-of-notables-after-raimondo-controversy.ece|title=La Salle Academy removes all photos from Wall of Notables after Raimondo controversy|author=Tom Mooney|publisher=providencejournal.com|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> allowed to attend the Catholic school, where she was valedictorian.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stanton |first=Mike |title=Challenging the pension system |url=http://digital.olivesoftware.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=ProvidenceJournal&BaseHref=TPJ%2F2011%2F04%2F10&ViewMode=HTML&PageLabelPrint=A1&EntityId=Ar00101|date=April 10, 2011 |work=The Providence Journal |accessdate=July 6, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nRaimondo graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] (AB) degree ''[[magna cum laude]]'' in Economics from [[Harvard College]] in 1993, where she served on the staff of ''[[The Harvard Crimson]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1992/12/7/six-harvard-students-win-rhodes-pharvard/?page=single|title=Six Harvard Students Win Rhodes|website=www.thecrimson.com}}</ref> She attended [[New College, Oxford]] as a [[Rhodes Scholarship|Rhodes Scholar]], where she received a [[Master of Arts]] (MA) degree and [[Doctor of Philosophy]] in 2002 in Sociology.<ref name=dphil>{{cite thesis|degree=DPhil|publisher=University of Oxford|url=http://solo.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/OXVU1:LSCOP_OX:oxfaleph015550334|doi=|title=Determinants of single motherhood in the United States|first= Gina|last=Raimondo|date=2002|id={{EThOS|uk.bl.ethos.270468}}|website=bodleian.ox.ac.uk|oclc=52794176}}</ref> Her doctoral thesis was on [[single parent|single motherhood]] and supervised by [[Stephen Nickell]] and Anne H. Gauthier while she was a postgraduate student of [[New College, Oxford]].<ref name=dphil/><ref name=yale>{{cite web|url=http://www.yale.edu/about/raimondo.html|title=Gina M. Raimondo, University Leadership |work=yale.edu|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Raimondo received her [[Juris Doctor]] (JD) degree from [[Yale Law School]] in 1998.<ref name=yale/>\n\n==Early career==\nFollowing her graduation from [[Yale Law School]], Raimondo served as a law clerk to federal Judge [[Kimba Wood]] of the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York]]. Later, Raimondo acted as Senior Vice President for Fund Development at the Manhattan offices of Village Ventures, a venture capital firm based in [[Williamstown, Massachusetts]], and backed by [[Bain Capital]] and Highland Capital Groups.<ref>{{cite news |last=McDonald |first=Michael |title=Gina Raimondo Math Convinces Rhode Island of America's Prospects |url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-01-18/gina-raimondo-math-convinces-rhode-island-of-america-s-prospects.html |date=January 18, 2012 |work=Business Week |accessdate=February 12, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226235648/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-01-18/gina-raimondo-math-convinces-rhode-island-of-america-s-prospects.html |archivedate=February 26, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youngstartup.com/lifesciences07/bio.php?id=828|title=The 2007 Life Sciences & Healthcare Venture Summit|publisher=youngstartup.com|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Raimondo returned to Rhode Island in 2000 to co-found the state's first venture capital firm, Point Judith Capital. Point Judith subsequently relocated its offices to Boston, Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.golocalprov.com/news/pt.-judith-payment|title=GoLocalProv - State Pension Fund Pays $570,000 to Raimondo's Former Firm|work=GoLocalProv|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> At Point Judith, Raimondo served as a general partner covering health care investments; she retains some executive duties with the firm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.golocalprov.com/politics/golocal-voters-guide-gt-candidates-gina-raimondo|title=GoLocalProv - GoLocal Voter's Guide - GT Candidates: Gina Raimondo|work=GoLocalProv|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Walsh |first=Mary Williams |title=The Little State With a Big Mess |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/23/business/for-rhode-island-the-pension-crisis-is-now.html?pagewanted=all |date=October 22, 2001 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=January 28, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==General treasurer of Rhode Island==\nOn November 2, 2010, Raimondo defeated her Republican opponent, Kernan King, for the office of general treasurer. She defeated Mr. King by a wide margin of 62 percent to 38 percent. She received 201,625 votes, more than any other Rhode Island candidate during the 2010 elections.<ref>[http://www.ri.gov/election/results/2010/general_election/ ''2010 General Election Statewide Summary''], Rhode Island Board of Elections, November 17, 2010.</ref> She is the second woman, after Republican Nancy J. Mayer of Bristol, to serve in that capacity since 1940.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sos.ri.gov/library/history/treasurers/|title=Office of the Secretary of State: Nellie M. Gorbea: State Library|publisher=ri.gov|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Pension policies===\n[[File:Gina Raimondo.png|thumb|Raimondo in 2012]]\nDuring her first year as General Treasurer, she headed the effort to reform Rhode Island's [[Public employee pension plans in the United States|public employee pension system]], which was 48% funded in 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last=Corkery |first=Michael |title=Softer Approach on Pension Problem |url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424053111904233404576465003932842770\n |date=July 25, 2011 |work=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=December 5, 2012 }}</ref> In April 2011, Raimondo led the state retirement board to reduce the state's assumed rate of return on pension investments from 8.25 percent to 7.5 percent.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nesi |first=Ted |title=Providence pension tab tops $900M with lower investment rate |url=http://blogs.wpri.com/2012/01/31/providence-pension-tab-tops-900m-after-return-rate-lowered/ |date=January 31, 2012 |publisher=WPRI |accessdate=July 6, 2012 }}</ref> In May 2011, Raimondo released \"Truth in Numbers\", a report that advocated for benefit cuts as the solution to Rhode Island's pension problems, and she helped lead the effort to cut pensions, along with [[Gordon Fox]], who was then speaker of the House.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sardelli |first=Melissa |title=Report reveals scope of pension crisis |url=http://www.wpri.com/dpp/news/local_news/providence/report-reveals-scope-of-pension-crisis |date=May 23, 2011 |publisher=WPRI |accessdate=October 14, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111018064133/http://www.wpri.com/dpp/news/local_news/providence/report-reveals-scope-of-pension-crisis |archivedate=October 18, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref> The Rhode Island Retirement Security Act (RIRSA) was enacted by the General Assembly on November 17, 2012, with bipartisan support in both chambers.  The next day, [[Lincoln Chafee]] signed RIRSA into law. A Brown University poll, conducted in December 2011, found that 60 percent of Rhode Island residents supported the pension reform.<ref>{{cite news |last=McDonald |first=Michael |title=Gina Raimondo Math Convinces Rhode Island Of America's Prospects With Debt |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-10/gina-raimondo-math-convinces-rhode-island-of-america-s-prospects-with-debt.html |date=January 10, 2012 |work=Bloomberg |accessdate=July 3, 2012 }}</ref>  The legality of RIRSA was challenged in court by the public employee unions, but a settlement was reached in June 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/article/20150605/NEWS/150609563|title=Report claims R.I. employee pension system 'mismanaged', has 'squandered billions'|last=Gregg|first=Katherine|newspaper=providencejournal.com|language=en|access-date=2017-01-24}}</ref>\n\nUnder Raimondo's tenure the pension fund was criticized for underperforming its peers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.wpri.com/2013/08/27/ri-pension-fund-again-lags-its-peers-with-return-of-11-1/|title=RI pension fund again lags its peers with return of 11.1% - WPRI.com Blogs|publisher=wpri.com|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref>  Some of Raimondo's critics attributed the underperformance to a sharp increase in fees paid to hedge fund managers, while her supporters argue investments in hedge funds stabilize investments during market downturns for more consistent returns over time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/edwardsiedle/2013/04/16/rhode-island-pensioners-3-colas-will-help-pay-wall-street-high-rollers-4-fees/|title=Rhode Island Pensioners 3% COLA Will Go To Pay Wall Street 4%+ Fees|author=Edward \"Ted\" Siedle|date=April 16, 2013|work=Forbes|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Municipalities===\nRaimondo created the Ocean State Investment Pool (OSIP), a low-cost investment vehicle intended to help the state and municipalities better manage and improve the investment performance of their liquid assets, which are used for day-to-day operations including payroll and operating expenses. $500 million in funds could be eligible for the program, which would enable Treasury \"to extend its expertise to municipalities and improve investment returns by creating economies of scale.\"<ref>[http://www.ri.gov/press/view/16376 \u201cPress Release: Ocean State Investment Pool Open to Municipalities\u201d], Rhode Island Office of the General Treasurer, April 23, 2012.</ref> The program launched in April 23, 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=State launches investment pool with Fidelity |url=http://pbn.com/State-launches-investment-pool-with-Fidelity,67092 |date=March 24, 2012 |work=PBN |accessdate=December 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Transparency===\n{{Essay-like|section|date=September 2018}}\nIn 2011, Raimondo led a review of the state's bond disclosure practices and updated the information statement and related bond disclosure information that will accompany future bond offerings.<ref>[http://www.ri.gov/press/view/14289 \u201cPress Release: State Increases Transparency, Launches Investor Relations Portal\"], Rhode Island Office of the General Treasurer, July 14, 2011.</ref> In conjunction with the changes to bond disclosure policies, Raimondo launched the state's first 'Investor Relations Portal', which includes financial information and related reports from the office of the general treasurer, the Employees' Retirement System of Rhode Island, the state budget office, the department of revenue, and the state office of the auditor general.<ref>{{cite news |title=R.I. launches site on state's financial information |url=http://pbn.com/RI-launches-site-on-states-financial-information,59829 |date=July 15, 2011 |work=PBN |accessdate=December 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAfter a struggle to get the information in August 2013 ''The Providence Journal'' got info from some funds \"Among the information redacted: what companies the funds invest in, past returns and withdrawal rates, how much the partners earn and their personal stakes in their funds, even such details as the identities of traders and the funds' outside auditing and accounting firms.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/breaking-news/content/20130803-in-hedge-fund-world-transparency-takes-a-hit.ece|title=In hedge fund world, transparency takes a hit|date=3 August 2013|last=Stanton|first=Mike|publisher=[[The Providence Journal]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110050553/http://www.providencejournal.com/breaking-news/content/20130803-in-hedge-fund-world-transparency-takes-a-hit.ece|archivedate=10 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn July 11, 2018, the SEC named Raimondo in Pay-to-Play Scheme with Investment Firm Oaktree.\n\n===Payday lending===\nDuring the Rhode Island General Assembly's 2012 session, Raimondo advocated for a decrease in the maximum allowable interest rate on [[payday loans]] in Rhode Island. She hosted a roundtable discussion with then Providence Mayor [[Angel Taveras]] and members of the Rhode Island Payday Reform Coalition.<ref>{{cite news |last=Marcello |first=Philip |title='Payday' loan rates assailed |url=http://digital.olivesoftware.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=ProvidenceJournal&BaseHref=TPJ%2F2012%2F04%2F18&ViewMode=HTML&PageLabelPrint=A1&EntityId=Ar00103 |date=April 18, 2012 |work=The Providence Journal |accessdate=December 5, 2012 }}</ref> Raimondo submitted letters to the Senate and House Corporations Committees in support of payday reform legislation. She wrote, \"Far too many families are facing financial challenges that might be mitigated or avoided through a greater understanding of personal finance,\" and \"payday loans exploit that lack of understanding\u2026. With numerous economic challenges, Rhode Island should not permit the sale of a financial product that traps so many customers in a cycle of debt.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Fitzpatrick |first=Ed |title=Military shows way on payday loans |url=http://digital.olivesoftware.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=ProvidenceJournal&BaseHref=TPJ%2F2012%2F03%2F25&ViewMode=HTML&PageLabelPrint=A2&EntityId=Ar00202 |date=March 25, 2012 |work=The Providence Journal |accessdate=December 5, 2012 }}</ref> Raimondo wrote an op-ed in the edition of May 29, 2012 of ''The Providence Journal'' in support of payday lending reform.<ref>{{cite news |last=Raimondo |first=Gina M. |title=Op-ed: Protect R.I. from these abusive lenders |url=http://digital.olivesoftware.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=ProvidenceJournal&BaseHref=TPJ/2012/05/29&PageLabelPrint=B6&EntityId=Ar01401&ViewMode=HTML |work=The Providence Journal |accessdate=December 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Governor of Rhode Island==\n[[File:Inauguration of Gina Raimondo 03.jpg|thumb|Raimondo at her inauguration]]\nRaimondo was elected governor of Rhode Island on November 4, 2014, winning 41% of the vote in a three-way race, defeating challengers [[Allan Fung]] (R) and [[Robert J. Healey]] of the Moderate Party. Raimondo is the first female governor of Rhode Island.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/05/us-usa-elections-rhodeisland-governor-idUSKBN0IP0AR20141105|title=Democrat Gina Raimondo becomes Rhode Island's first female governor|date=November 4, 2014|accessdate=April 15, 2015|agency=Reuters}}</ref> She is also one of nine [[List of female governors in the United States#List of Female State Governors|current female governors]] of the United States. During her first year as governor, she advocated expanding the state's Earned Income Tax Credit (EITC), raising the minimum wage, lowering the state's minimum corporate tax rate, and eliminating the tax on commercial energy use.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nRaimondo served as the Vice Chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]] for the [[United States gubernatorial elections, 2018|2018 election cycle]]<ref name=\":0\" /> and became Chair in 2019.<ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2019/01/24/she-didn-win-big-but-raimondo-reelection-signals-continuity-amid-rocky-rhode-island-politics/9bc8AQbL1f2Kh1rHYz8IqK/story.html She didn\u2019t win big. But Raimondo\u2019s reelection signals continuity amid rocky Rhode Island politics]</ref>\n\nOn March 28, 2020, [[New York (state)|New York]] Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] threatened Raimondo with a lawsuit over a new state quarantine policy, which would make sure people from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)|coronavirus]]-hit New York would [[self-quarantine]] for 14 days upon arrival in Rhode Island.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cuomo threatens to sue RI over new policy to find New Yorkers in the state |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/490019-cuomo-threatens-to-sue-ri-over-new-coronavirus-policy-targeting-ny |work=The Hill |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Cuomo threatens to sue Rhode Island if it doesn't ease up on New Yorkers during coronavirus pandemic |url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/905509/cuomo-threatens-sue-rhode-island-doesnt-ease-new-yorkers-during-coronavirus-pandemic |work=The Week |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> On March 29, Raimondo repealed the order that specifically referred to New Yorkers, and broadened it to include any out-of-state traveller entering Rhode Island with intent to stay.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Rhode Island forces all travelers from other states into self-quarantine |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2020/03/29/coronavirus-rhode-repeals-new-york-quarantine-order/2935755001/ |work=USA Today |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n===State government computer system failure===\nIn February 2017, Raimondo's Executive Secretary of Health and Human Services [[Elizabeth H. Roberts]] resigned from her post<ref name=\"Nesi\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wpri.com/news/health-secretary-elizabeth-roberts-resigns/|title=Health Secretary Elizabeth Roberts Resigns|last=Nesi|first=Ted|date=14 February 2017|work=CBS 12|access-date=26 November 2019}}</ref> due to the failed roll-out of the botched Unified Health Infrastructure Project (a new statewide computer network).<ref name=\"Nesi\"/> The disastrous UHIP computer network launch in September 2016 saw scores of people without access to government programs such as food stamps and child care due to glitches in the software, designed<ref name=\"Deloitte\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20170217/ri-gov-raimondo-deloitte-ceo-discuss-state-computer-woes-at-calif-conference|title=R.I. Gov. Raimondo, Deloitte CEO discuss state computer woes at Calif. conference|last=Pina|first=Alisha|date=17 February 2017|work=The Providence Journal|access-date=26 November 2019}}</ref> by [[Deloitte]]. This crash created a backlog of over 20,000 cases.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://turnto10.com/i-team/nbc-10-i-team-ris-health-secretary-elizabeth-roberts-resigns|title=NBC 10 I-Team: RI's Health Secretary Elizabeth Roberts resigns|last=Davis|first=Katie|date=14 November 2019|work=NBC News|access-date=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===RI DCYF fatalities and near-fatalities===\nUnder Governor Raimondo, the [[Rhode Island Department of Children, Youth & Families|Rhode Island DCYF]] has come under fire due to its relatively high rate of deaths and near-deaths of children in its care.<ref name=\"Doiron\">{{cite news |last1=Doiron |first1=Sarah |title=DCYF report: 8 child fatalities, 23 near fatalities in RI over two-year span |url=https://www.wpri.com/news/dcyf-report-8-child-fatalities-23-near-fatalities-in-ri-over-two-year-span/ |accessdate=22 November 2019 |publisher=CBS 12 News |date=20 August 2018}}</ref> In a period between January 2016 and December 2017, there were 31 fatalities or near fatalities of children in its care, with eight being confirmed fatal.<ref name=\"Doiron\"/>\n\nRaimondo appointed [[Trista Piccola]] as her new DCYF Director in January 2017. Piccola's term was marked by the death and near-deaths of children,<ref name=\"Doiron\" /> high staff turn-over rates,<ref name=\"Resende\">{{cite news |last1=Resende |first1=Patricia |title=RI Child Advocate recommends system overhaul after deaths of four children |url=https://turnto10.com/news/local/state-advocacy-group-releases-findings-after-deaths-of-four-children |accessdate=22 November 2019 |publisher=NBC 10 News |date=23 March 2017}}</ref> votes of no confidence,<ref name=\"confidence\">{{cite news |title=DCYF Director responds after union's 'no confidence' vote |url=https://turnto10.com/news/local/dcyf-union-votes-no-confidence-in-director-after-warwick-childs-death |accessdate=22 November 2019 |agency=NBC 10 News |date=21 November 2019}}</ref> and high budget deficits.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rhode Island DCYF projects $18M budget deficit |url=http://www.997wpro.com/2019/05/06/rhode-island-dcyf-projects-18m-budget-deficit/ |accessdate=22 November 2019 |publisher=WPRO/Associated Press |date=6 May 2019}}</ref> Rep. [[Patricia Serpa]] and Rep. [[Charlene Lima]] called for the resignation of Piccola, which finally occurred in July 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wpri.com/news/local-news/providence/dcyf-director-piccola-to-leave-post/|title=DCYF Director Piccola to leave post|last=Kalunian|first=Kim|date=10 July 2019|work=CBS 12 News|access-date=21 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://turnto10.com/news/local/dcyf-director-expected-to-leave-the-department|title=DCYF director steps down|last=|first=|date=10 July 2019|work=NBC 10 News|access-date=21 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20190710/dcyf-director-trista-piccola-to-depart-after-tumultuous-2xbd-year-tenure|title=DCYF Director Trista Piccola to depart after tumultuous 2\u00bd-year tenure|last=Mooney|first=Tom|date=10 July 2019|work=The Providence Journal|access-date=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Approval ratings===\n\nSince assuming office, Raimondo has consistently ranked in the bottom four in approval ratings for all governors in the United States.<ref>https://morningconsult.com/governor-rankings/</ref>\n\n==Community service==\nRaimondo serves as vice chair of the board of directors of Crossroads Rhode Island, the state's largest homeless services organization. Until 2011, she was an administrator [[Women & Infants Hospital of Rhode Island|Women and Infants Hospital]] and chair of its Quality Committee. She has served on the boards of [[La Salle Academy, Providence|La Salle Academy]] and Family Service of Rhode Island.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n==Fellowships and awards==\n\nRaimondo is a member of the [[Council on Foreign Relations]] and an [[Aspen Institute]] Rodel fellow. She was awarded an honorary degree from [[Bryant University]], in 2012; and has received awards from the northern Rhode Island chamber of commerce and the [[YWCA]] of northern Rhode Island. Raimondo was elected alumni fellow at Yale, in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yale.edu/board-trustees/current-trustees/gina-raimondo|title=Board of Trustees: Current Trustees|publisher=yale.edu|accessdate=September 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Rhode Island General Treasurer Election, 2010\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Democratic\n|'''Gina Raimondo'''\n|201,625\n|62.1\n|-\n|Republican\n|Kernan King\n|122,860\n|37.9\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Rhode Island Governor Democratic Primary Election, 2014\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Democratic\n|'''Gina Raimondo'''\n|53,990\n|42.1\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Angel Taveras\n|37,326\n|29.1\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Clay Pell\n|34,515\n|26.9\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Todd Giroux\n|2,264\n|1.8\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Rhode Island Governor Election, 2014\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Democratic\n|'''Gina Raimondo'''\n|131,899\n|40.7\n|-\n|Republican\n|Allan Fung\n|117,428\n|36.2\n|-\n|Moderate\n|Robert Healey, Jr.\n|69,278\n|21.4\n|-\n|Independent\n|Kate Fletcher\n|3,483\n|1.1\n|-\n|Independent\n|Leon Kayarian\n|1,228\n|0.4\n|-\n|Write-ins\n|Write-ins\n|739\n|0.2\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Rhode Island Governor Election, 2018\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Democratic\n|'''Gina Raimondo'''\n|198,122\n|52.8\n|-\n|Republican\n|Allan Fung\n|139,932\n|37.3\n|-\n|Independent\n|Joe Trillo\n|16,532\n|4.4\n|-\n|Moderate\n|William Gilbert\n|10,155\n|2.7\n|-\n|Independent\n|Luis Munoz\n|6,223\n|1.7\n|-\n|Independent\n|Anne Armstrong\n|4,191\n|1.1\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nOn November 1, 2001, Raimondo married Andrew Kind Moffit, in Providence, Rhode Island.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/12/02/style/weddings-gina-raimondo-andrew-moffit.html|title=WEDDINGS -  Gina Raimondo, Andrew Moffit |date=December 2, 2001|work=The New York Times|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> The couple have two children, Cecilia and Thompson Moffit. The family resides on the east side of Providence.<ref>http://www.gov.ri.gov/about</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of female governors in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal box|Rhode Island}}\n* [http://www.governor.ri.gov/ Rhode Island Governor Gina Raimondo] official government site\n* [https://ginaraimondo.com Gina Raimondo for Governor] official campaign site\n*{{Curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/Rhode_Island/Government/Executive/Governor_Gina_Raimondo}}\n*{{C-SPAN|ginaraimondo}}\n*[https://sosri.access.preservica.com/uncategorized/digitalFile_2f7f2f64-4c2e-48c2-8e35-658c6dfcee75/ Governor Gina M. Raimondo Inauguration Program] from the Rhode Island State Archives\n\n{{commons category|Gina Raimondo}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Frank T. Caprio|Frank Caprio]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[List of Governors of Rhode Island|Governor of Rhode Island]]|years=[[Rhode Island gubernatorial election, 2014|2014]], [[Rhode Island gubernatorial election, 2018|2018]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jay Inslee]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Phil Murphy]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lincoln Chafee]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Governors of Rhode Island|Governor of Rhode Island]]|years=2015\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Mike Pence]]|as=[[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]]}}\n{{s-ttl|rows=2|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Within Rhode Island}}\n{{s-aft|after=Mayor of city<br>in which event is held}}\n|-\n{{s-aft|after=Otherwise {{Incumbent U.S. House Speaker}}<br>{{nowrap|''as [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives]]''}}}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Roy Cooper]]|as=[[List of Governors of North Carolina|Governor of North Carolina]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Outside Rhode Island}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Phil Scott (politician)|Phil Scott]]|as=[[List of Governors of Vermont|Governor of Vermont]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of Rhode Island}} \n{{Current U.S. governors}}\n{{Private equity investors}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raimondo, Gina}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of New College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American business executives]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:American venture capitalists]]\n[[Category:American women business executives]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Governors of Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Harvard Crimson alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:La Salle Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Smithfield, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island Democrats]]\n[[Category:State treasurers of Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Women in Rhode Island politics]]\n[[Category:Women state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Yale Law School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{short description|75th Governor of Rhode Island}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Gina Raimondo\n|image        = Governor Gina Raimondo of Rhode Island.jpg\n|order        = 75th [[Governor of Rhode Island]]\n|lieutenant   = [[Daniel McKee]]\n|term_start   = January 6, 2015\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Lincoln Chafee]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = Chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]]\n|term_start1  = December 1, 2018\n|term_end1    = December 4, 2019\n|predecessor1 = [[Jay Inslee]]\n|successor1   = [[Phil Murphy]]\n|office2      = General Treasurer of Rhode Island\n|governor2    = Lincoln Chafee\n|term_start2  = January 4, 2011\n|term_end2    = January 6, 2015\n|predecessor2 = [[Frank T. Caprio|Frank Caprio]]\n|successor2   = [[Seth Magaziner]]\n|birth_name   = Gina Marie Raimondo\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1971|5|17}}\n|birth_place  = [[Smithfield, Rhode Island]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Andrew Moffit|2001}}\n|children     = 2\n|education    = [[La Salle Academy, Providence|LaSalle Academy]]<br>[[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|AB]])<br>[[New College, Oxford]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|DPhil]])<br>[[Yale University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]]) \n}}\n'''Gina Marie Raimondo''' ({{IPAc-en|r|\u0259|\u02c8|m|\u0252|n|d|o\u028a}}; born May 17, 1971) is an American politician and venture capitalist serving, since 2015, as the [[Governor of Rhode Island|75th]] [[Governor of Rhode Island]]. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], she is the first woman to serve as Governor of Rhode Island.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/democrat-gina-raimondo-wins-rhode-island-governor-race-032616738.html;_ylt=AwrBTzkMVFpU7mAAlqZx.9w4|title=Democrat Gina Raimondo becomes Rhode Island's first female governor|date=November 5, 2014|work=Yahoo News|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Prior to her election, she served as General Treasurer of [[Rhode Island]] from 2011 to 2015 and was the second woman to hold the office. She was selected as the Democratic candidate for Rhode Island's governorship in the [[2014 Rhode Island gubernatorial election|2014 election]]. Raimondo won the election on November 4, 2014, with 41% of the vote, in a three-way race, against the Mayor of [[Cranston, Rhode Island|Cranston]], Republican [[Allan Fung]], and businessman [[Robert J. Healey|Robert Healey]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sullivan|first1=Sean|title=Raimondo launches campaign for Rhode Island governor|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2013/12/18/raimondo-launches-campaign-for-rhode-island-governor/|work=The Washington Post|date=December 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nRaimondo was elected to serve as the Vice Chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]] for the [[2018 United States gubernatorial elections|2018 election cycle]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20171204/raimondo-to-help-lead-democratic-governors-group|title=Raimondo to help lead Democratic Governors group|last=Gregg|first=Katherine|work=providencejournal.com|access-date=2017-12-05|language=en}}</ref> She was the Chair of the Democratic Governors Association, and was only the second woman to serve in that position.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20181201/ris-raimondo-elected-to-lead-democratic-governors---audio|title=R.I.'s Raimondo elected to lead Democratic governors {{!}} audio|last=Gregg|first=Katherine|website=providencejournal.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-25}}</ref> Raimondo ran for and won reelection to a second term in [[2018 Rhode Island gubernatorial election|2018]], and becoming the first candidate to secure a majority of votes for that office since [[2006 Rhode Island gubernatorial election|2006]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nGina Marie Raimondo was born May 17, 1971<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ballotpedia.org/Gina_Raimondo|title=Gina Raimondo|publisher=ballotpedia.org|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> in [[Smithfield, Rhode Island]], where she later grew up. Of Italian descent, she is the youngest of Josephine (Piro) and Joseph Raimondo's three children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://funeralhomeweb.net/default.aspx?MemberId=134509&FLVId=|title=Nardolillo Funeral Home Published an Obituary for Joseph  Raimondo|work=Nardolillo Funeral Home Website|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ginaraimondo.com/about|title=About Gina|work=Gina Raimondo for RI|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Her father worked for a watch company. Raimondo graduated from [[La Salle Academy, Providence|LaSalle Academy]], in Providence, as one of the first girls<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/breaking-news/content/20141002-la-salle-academy-removes-all-photos-from-wall-of-notables-after-raimondo-controversy.ece|title=La Salle Academy removes all photos from Wall of Notables after Raimondo controversy|author=Tom Mooney|publisher=providencejournal.com|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> allowed to attend the Catholic school, where she was valedictorian.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stanton |first=Mike |title=Challenging the pension system |url=http://digital.olivesoftware.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=ProvidenceJournal&BaseHref=TPJ%2F2011%2F04%2F10&ViewMode=HTML&PageLabelPrint=A1&EntityId=Ar00101|date=April 10, 2011 |work=The Providence Journal |accessdate=July 6, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nRaimondo graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] (AB) degree ''[[magna cum laude]]'' in Economics from [[Harvard College]] in 1993, where she served on the staff of ''[[The Harvard Crimson]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1992/12/7/six-harvard-students-win-rhodes-pharvard/?page=single|title=Six Harvard Students Win Rhodes|website=www.thecrimson.com}}</ref> She attended [[New College, Oxford]] as a [[Rhodes Scholarship|Rhodes Scholar]], where she received a [[Master of Arts]] (MA) degree and [[Doctor of Philosophy]] in 2002 in Sociology.<ref name=dphil>{{cite thesis|degree=DPhil|publisher=University of Oxford|url=http://solo.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/OXVU1:LSCOP_OX:oxfaleph015550334|doi=|title=Determinants of single motherhood in the United States|first= Gina|last=Raimondo|date=2002|id={{EThOS|uk.bl.ethos.270468}}|website=bodleian.ox.ac.uk|oclc=52794176}}</ref> Her doctoral thesis was on [[single parent|single motherhood]] and supervised by [[Stephen Nickell]] and Anne H. Gauthier while she was a postgraduate student of [[New College, Oxford]].<ref name=dphil/><ref name=yale>{{cite web|url=http://www.yale.edu/about/raimondo.html|title=Gina M. Raimondo, University Leadership |work=yale.edu|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Raimondo received her [[Juris Doctor]] (JD) degree from [[Yale Law School]] in 1998.<ref name=yale/>\n\n==Early career==\nFollowing her graduation from [[Yale Law School]], Raimondo served as a law clerk to federal Judge [[Kimba Wood]] of the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York]]. Later, Raimondo acted as Senior Vice President for Fund Development at the Manhattan offices of Village Ventures, a venture capital firm based in [[Williamstown, Massachusetts]], and backed by [[Bain Capital]] and Highland Capital Groups.<ref>{{cite news |last=McDonald |first=Michael |title=Gina Raimondo Math Convinces Rhode Island of America's Prospects |url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-01-18/gina-raimondo-math-convinces-rhode-island-of-america-s-prospects.html |date=January 18, 2012 |work=Business Week |accessdate=February 12, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226235648/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-01-18/gina-raimondo-math-convinces-rhode-island-of-america-s-prospects.html |archivedate=February 26, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youngstartup.com/lifesciences07/bio.php?id=828|title=The 2007 Life Sciences & Healthcare Venture Summit|publisher=youngstartup.com|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Raimondo returned to Rhode Island in 2000 to co-found the state's first venture capital firm, Point Judith Capital. Point Judith subsequently relocated its offices to Boston, Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.golocalprov.com/news/pt.-judith-payment|title=GoLocalProv - State Pension Fund Pays $570,000 to Raimondo's Former Firm|work=GoLocalProv|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> At Point Judith, Raimondo served as a general partner covering health care investments; she retains some executive duties with the firm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.golocalprov.com/politics/golocal-voters-guide-gt-candidates-gina-raimondo|title=GoLocalProv - GoLocal Voter's Guide - GT Candidates: Gina Raimondo|work=GoLocalProv|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Walsh |first=Mary Williams |title=The Little State With a Big Mess |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/23/business/for-rhode-island-the-pension-crisis-is-now.html?pagewanted=all |date=October 22, 2001 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=January 28, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==General treasurer of Rhode Island==\nOn November 2, 2010, Raimondo defeated her Republican opponent, Kernan King, for the office of general treasurer. She defeated Mr. King by a wide margin of 62 percent to 38 percent. She received 201,625 votes, more than any other Rhode Island candidate during the 2010 elections.<ref>[http://www.ri.gov/election/results/2010/general_election/ ''2010 General Election Statewide Summary''], Rhode Island Board of Elections, November 17, 2010.</ref> She is the second woman, after Republican Nancy J. Mayer of Bristol, to serve in that capacity since 1940.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sos.ri.gov/library/history/treasurers/|title=Office of the Secretary of State: Nellie M. Gorbea: State Library|publisher=ri.gov|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Pension policies===\n[[File:Gina Raimondo.png|thumb|Raimondo in 2012]]\nDuring her first year as General Treasurer, she headed the effort to reform Rhode Island's [[Public employee pension plans in the United States|public employee pension system]], which was 48% funded in 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last=Corkery |first=Michael |title=Softer Approach on Pension Problem |url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424053111904233404576465003932842770\n |date=July 25, 2011 |work=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=December 5, 2012 }}</ref> In April 2011, Raimondo led the state retirement board to reduce the state's assumed rate of return on pension investments from 8.25 percent to 7.5 percent.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nesi |first=Ted |title=Providence pension tab tops $900M with lower investment rate |url=http://blogs.wpri.com/2012/01/31/providence-pension-tab-tops-900m-after-return-rate-lowered/ |date=January 31, 2012 |publisher=WPRI |accessdate=July 6, 2012 }}</ref> In May 2011, Raimondo released \"Truth in Numbers\", a report that advocated for benefit cuts as the solution to Rhode Island's pension problems, and she helped lead the effort to cut pensions, along with [[Gordon Fox]], who was then speaker of the House.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sardelli |first=Melissa |title=Report reveals scope of pension crisis |url=http://www.wpri.com/dpp/news/local_news/providence/report-reveals-scope-of-pension-crisis |date=May 23, 2011 |publisher=WPRI |accessdate=October 14, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111018064133/http://www.wpri.com/dpp/news/local_news/providence/report-reveals-scope-of-pension-crisis |archivedate=October 18, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref> The Rhode Island Retirement Security Act (RIRSA) was enacted by the General Assembly on November 17, 2012, with bipartisan support in both chambers.  The next day, [[Lincoln Chafee]] signed RIRSA into law. A Brown University poll, conducted in December 2011, found that 60 percent of Rhode Island residents supported the pension reform.<ref>{{cite news |last=McDonald |first=Michael |title=Gina Raimondo Math Convinces Rhode Island Of America's Prospects With Debt |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-10/gina-raimondo-math-convinces-rhode-island-of-america-s-prospects-with-debt.html |date=January 10, 2012 |work=Bloomberg |accessdate=July 3, 2012 }}</ref>  The legality of RIRSA was challenged in court by the public employee unions, but a settlement was reached in June 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/article/20150605/NEWS/150609563|title=Report claims R.I. employee pension system 'mismanaged', has 'squandered billions'|last=Gregg|first=Katherine|newspaper=providencejournal.com|language=en|access-date=2017-01-24}}</ref>\n\nUnder Raimondo's tenure the pension fund was criticized for underperforming its peers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.wpri.com/2013/08/27/ri-pension-fund-again-lags-its-peers-with-return-of-11-1/|title=RI pension fund again lags its peers with return of 11.1% - WPRI.com Blogs|publisher=wpri.com|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref>  Some of Raimondo's critics attributed the underperformance to a sharp increase in fees paid to hedge fund managers, while her supporters argue investments in hedge funds stabilize investments during market downturns for more consistent returns over time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/edwardsiedle/2013/04/16/rhode-island-pensioners-3-colas-will-help-pay-wall-street-high-rollers-4-fees/|title=Rhode Island Pensioners 3% COLA Will Go To Pay Wall Street 4%+ Fees|author=Edward \"Ted\" Siedle|date=April 16, 2013|work=Forbes|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Municipalities===\nRaimondo created the Ocean State Investment Pool (OSIP), a low-cost investment vehicle intended to help the state and municipalities better manage and improve the investment performance of their liquid assets, which are used for day-to-day operations including payroll and operating expenses. $500 million in funds could be eligible for the program, which would enable Treasury \"to extend its expertise to municipalities and improve investment returns by creating economies of scale.\"<ref>[http://www.ri.gov/press/view/16376 \u201cPress Release: Ocean State Investment Pool Open to Municipalities\u201d], Rhode Island Office of the General Treasurer, April 23, 2012.</ref> The program launched in April 23, 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=State launches investment pool with Fidelity |url=http://pbn.com/State-launches-investment-pool-with-Fidelity,67092 |date=March 24, 2012 |work=PBN |accessdate=December 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Transparency===\n{{Essay-like|section|date=September 2018}}\nIn 2011, Raimondo led a review of the state's bond disclosure practices and updated the information statement and related bond disclosure information that will accompany future bond offerings.<ref>[http://www.ri.gov/press/view/14289 \u201cPress Release: State Increases Transparency, Launches Investor Relations Portal\"], Rhode Island Office of the General Treasurer, July 14, 2011.</ref> In conjunction with the changes to bond disclosure policies, Raimondo launched the state's first 'Investor Relations Portal', which includes financial information and related reports from the office of the general treasurer, the Employees' Retirement System of Rhode Island, the state budget office, the department of revenue, and the state office of the auditor general.<ref>{{cite news |title=R.I. launches site on state's financial information |url=http://pbn.com/RI-launches-site-on-states-financial-information,59829 |date=July 15, 2011 |work=PBN |accessdate=December 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAfter a struggle to get the information in August 2013 ''The Providence Journal'' got info from some funds \"Among the information redacted: what companies the funds invest in, past returns and withdrawal rates, how much the partners earn and their personal stakes in their funds, even such details as the identities of traders and the funds' outside auditing and accounting firms.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.providencejournal.com/breaking-news/content/20130803-in-hedge-fund-world-transparency-takes-a-hit.ece|title=In hedge fund world, transparency takes a hit|date=3 August 2013|last=Stanton|first=Mike|publisher=[[The Providence Journal]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110050553/http://www.providencejournal.com/breaking-news/content/20130803-in-hedge-fund-world-transparency-takes-a-hit.ece|archivedate=10 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn July 11, 2018, the SEC named Raimondo in Pay-to-Play Scheme with Investment Firm Oaktree.\n\n===Payday lending===\nDuring the Rhode Island General Assembly's 2012 session, Raimondo advocated for a decrease in the maximum allowable interest rate on [[payday loans]] in Rhode Island. She hosted a roundtable discussion with then Providence Mayor [[Angel Taveras]] and members of the Rhode Island Payday Reform Coalition.<ref>{{cite news |last=Marcello |first=Philip |title='Payday' loan rates assailed |url=http://digital.olivesoftware.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=ProvidenceJournal&BaseHref=TPJ%2F2012%2F04%2F18&ViewMode=HTML&PageLabelPrint=A1&EntityId=Ar00103 |date=April 18, 2012 |work=The Providence Journal |accessdate=December 5, 2012 }}</ref> Raimondo submitted letters to the Senate and House Corporations Committees in support of payday reform legislation. She wrote, \"Far too many families are facing financial challenges that might be mitigated or avoided through a greater understanding of personal finance,\" and \"payday loans exploit that lack of understanding\u2026. With numerous economic challenges, Rhode Island should not permit the sale of a financial product that traps so many customers in a cycle of debt.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Fitzpatrick |first=Ed |title=Military shows way on payday loans |url=http://digital.olivesoftware.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=ProvidenceJournal&BaseHref=TPJ%2F2012%2F03%2F25&ViewMode=HTML&PageLabelPrint=A2&EntityId=Ar00202 |date=March 25, 2012 |work=The Providence Journal |accessdate=December 5, 2012 }}</ref> Raimondo wrote an op-ed in the edition of May 29, 2012 of ''The Providence Journal'' in support of payday lending reform.<ref>{{cite news |last=Raimondo |first=Gina M. |title=Op-ed: Protect R.I. from these abusive lenders |url=http://digital.olivesoftware.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=ProvidenceJournal&BaseHref=TPJ/2012/05/29&PageLabelPrint=B6&EntityId=Ar01401&ViewMode=HTML |work=The Providence Journal |accessdate=December 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Governor of Rhode Island==\n[[File:Inauguration of Gina Raimondo 03.jpg|thumb|Raimondo at her inauguration]]\nRaimondo was elected governor of Rhode Island on November 4, 2014, winning 41% of the vote in a three-way race, defeating challengers [[Allan Fung]] (R) and [[Robert J. Healey]] of the Moderate Party. Raimondo is the first female governor of Rhode Island.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/05/us-usa-elections-rhodeisland-governor-idUSKBN0IP0AR20141105|title=Democrat Gina Raimondo becomes Rhode Island's first female governor|date=November 4, 2014|accessdate=April 15, 2015|agency=Reuters}}</ref> She is also one of nine [[List of female governors in the United States#List of Female State Governors|current female governors]] of the United States. During her first year as governor, she advocated expanding the state's Earned Income Tax Credit (EITC), raising the minimum wage, lowering the state's minimum corporate tax rate, and eliminating the tax on commercial energy use.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nRaimondo served as the Vice Chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]] for the [[United States gubernatorial elections, 2018|2018 election cycle]]<ref name=\":0\" /> and became Chair in 2019.<ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2019/01/24/she-didn-win-big-but-raimondo-reelection-signals-continuity-amid-rocky-rhode-island-politics/9bc8AQbL1f2Kh1rHYz8IqK/story.html She didn\u2019t win big. But Raimondo\u2019s reelection signals continuity amid rocky Rhode Island politics]</ref>\n\nOn March 28, 2020, [[New York (state)|New York]] Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] threatened Raimondo with a lawsuit over a new state quarantine policy, which would make sure people from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)|coronavirus]]-hit New York would [[self-quarantine]] for 14 days upon arrival in Rhode Island.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cuomo threatens to sue RI over new policy to find New Yorkers in the state |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/490019-cuomo-threatens-to-sue-ri-over-new-coronavirus-policy-targeting-ny |work=The Hill |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Cuomo threatens to sue Rhode Island if it doesn't ease up on New Yorkers during coronavirus pandemic |url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/905509/cuomo-threatens-sue-rhode-island-doesnt-ease-new-yorkers-during-coronavirus-pandemic |work=The Week |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> On March 29, Raimondo repealed the order that specifically referred to New Yorkers, and broadened it to include any out-of-state traveller entering Rhode Island with intent to stay.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Rhode Island forces all travelers from other states into self-quarantine |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2020/03/29/coronavirus-rhode-repeals-new-york-quarantine-order/2935755001/ |work=USA Today |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n===State government computer system failure===\nIn February 2017, Raimondo's Executive Secretary of Health and Human Services [[Elizabeth H. Roberts]] resigned from her post<ref name=\"Nesi\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wpri.com/news/health-secretary-elizabeth-roberts-resigns/|title=Health Secretary Elizabeth Roberts Resigns|last=Nesi|first=Ted|date=14 February 2017|work=CBS 12|access-date=26 November 2019}}</ref> due to the failed roll-out of the botched Unified Health Infrastructure Project (a new statewide computer network).<ref name=\"Nesi\"/> The disastrous UHIP computer network launch in September 2016 saw scores of people without access to government programs such as food stamps and child care due to glitches in the software, designed<ref name=\"Deloitte\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20170217/ri-gov-raimondo-deloitte-ceo-discuss-state-computer-woes-at-calif-conference|title=R.I. Gov. Raimondo, Deloitte CEO discuss state computer woes at Calif. conference|last=Pina|first=Alisha|date=17 February 2017|work=The Providence Journal|access-date=26 November 2019}}</ref> by [[Deloitte]]. This crash created a backlog of over 20,000 cases.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://turnto10.com/i-team/nbc-10-i-team-ris-health-secretary-elizabeth-roberts-resigns|title=NBC 10 I-Team: RI's Health Secretary Elizabeth Roberts resigns|last=Davis|first=Katie|date=14 November 2019|work=NBC News|access-date=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===RI DCYF fatalities and near-fatalities===\nUnder Governor Raimondo, the [[Rhode Island Department of Children, Youth & Families|Rhode Island DCYF]] has come under fire due to its relatively high rate of deaths and near-deaths of children in its care.<ref name=\"Doiron\">{{cite news |last1=Doiron |first1=Sarah |title=DCYF report: 8 child fatalities, 23 near fatalities in RI over two-year span |url=https://www.wpri.com/news/dcyf-report-8-child-fatalities-23-near-fatalities-in-ri-over-two-year-span/ |accessdate=22 November 2019 |publisher=CBS 12 News |date=20 August 2018}}</ref> In a period between January 2016 and December 2017, there were 31 fatalities or near fatalities of children in its care, with eight being confirmed fatal.<ref name=\"Doiron\"/>\n\nRaimondo appointed [[Trista Piccola]] as her new DCYF Director in January 2017. Piccola's term was marked by the death and near-deaths of children,<ref name=\"Doiron\" /> high staff turn-over rates,<ref name=\"Resende\">{{cite news |last1=Resende |first1=Patricia |title=RI Child Advocate recommends system overhaul after deaths of four children |url=https://turnto10.com/news/local/state-advocacy-group-releases-findings-after-deaths-of-four-children |accessdate=22 November 2019 |publisher=NBC 10 News |date=23 March 2017}}</ref> votes of no confidence,<ref name=\"confidence\">{{cite news |title=DCYF Director responds after union's 'no confidence' vote |url=https://turnto10.com/news/local/dcyf-union-votes-no-confidence-in-director-after-warwick-childs-death |accessdate=22 November 2019 |agency=NBC 10 News |date=21 November 2019}}</ref> and high budget deficits.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rhode Island DCYF projects $18M budget deficit |url=http://www.997wpro.com/2019/05/06/rhode-island-dcyf-projects-18m-budget-deficit/ |accessdate=22 November 2019 |publisher=WPRO/Associated Press |date=6 May 2019}}</ref> Rep. [[Patricia Serpa]] and Rep. [[Charlene Lima]] called for the resignation of Piccola, which finally occurred in July 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wpri.com/news/local-news/providence/dcyf-director-piccola-to-leave-post/|title=DCYF Director Piccola to leave post|last=Kalunian|first=Kim|date=10 July 2019|work=CBS 12 News|access-date=21 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://turnto10.com/news/local/dcyf-director-expected-to-leave-the-department|title=DCYF director steps down|last=|first=|date=10 July 2019|work=NBC 10 News|access-date=21 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20190710/dcyf-director-trista-piccola-to-depart-after-tumultuous-2xbd-year-tenure|title=DCYF Director Trista Piccola to depart after tumultuous 2\u00bd-year tenure|last=Mooney|first=Tom|date=10 July 2019|work=The Providence Journal|access-date=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Approval ratings===\n\nSince assuming office, Raimondo has consistently ranked in the bottom four in approval ratings for all governors in the United States.<ref>https://morningconsult.com/governor-rankings/</ref>\n\n==Community service==\nRaimondo serves as vice chair of the board of directors of Crossroads Rhode Island, the state's largest homeless services organization. Until 2011, she was an administrator [[Women & Infants Hospital of Rhode Island|Women and Infants Hospital]] and chair of its Quality Committee. She has served on the boards of [[La Salle Academy, Providence|La Salle Academy]] and Family Service of Rhode Island.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n==Fellowships and awards==\n\nRaimondo is a member of the [[Council on Foreign Relations]] and an [[Aspen Institute]] Rodel fellow. She was awarded an honorary degree from [[Bryant University]], in 2012; and has received awards from the northern Rhode Island chamber of commerce and the [[YWCA]] of northern Rhode Island. Raimondo was elected alumni fellow at Yale, in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yale.edu/board-trustees/current-trustees/gina-raimondo|title=Board of Trustees: Current Trustees|publisher=yale.edu|accessdate=September 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Rhode Island General Treasurer Election, 2010\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Democratic\n|'''Gina Raimondo'''\n|201,625\n|62.1\n|-\n|Republican\n|Kernan King\n|122,860\n|37.9\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Rhode Island Governor Democratic Primary Election, 2014\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Democratic\n|'''Gina Raimondo'''\n|53,990\n|42.1\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Angel Taveras\n|37,326\n|29.1\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Clay Pell\n|34,515\n|26.9\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Todd Giroux\n|2,264\n|1.8\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Rhode Island Governor Election, 2014\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Democratic\n|'''Gina Raimondo'''\n|131,899\n|40.7\n|-\n|Republican\n|Allan Fung\n|117,428\n|36.2\n|-\n|Moderate\n|Robert Healey, Jr.\n|69,278\n|21.4\n|-\n|Independent\n|Kate Fletcher\n|3,483\n|1.1\n|-\n|Independent\n|Leon Kayarian\n|1,228\n|0.4\n|-\n|Write-ins\n|Write-ins\n|739\n|0.2\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Rhode Island Governor Election, 2018\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Democratic\n|'''Gina Raimondo'''\n|198,122\n|52.8\n|-\n|Republican\n|Allan Fung\n|139,932\n|37.3\n|-\n|Independent\n|Joe Trillo\n|16,532\n|4.4\n|-\n|Moderate\n|William Gilbert\n|10,155\n|2.7\n|-\n|Independent\n|Luis Munoz\n|6,223\n|1.7\n|-\n|Independent\n|Anne Armstrong\n|4,191\n|1.1\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nOn November 1, 2001, Raimondo married Andrew Kind Moffit, in Providence, Rhode Island.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/12/02/style/weddings-gina-raimondo-andrew-moffit.html|title=WEDDINGS -  Gina Raimondo, Andrew Moffit |date=December 2, 2001|work=The New York Times|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> The couple have two children, Cecilia and Thompson Moffit. The family resides on the east side of Providence.<ref>http://www.gov.ri.gov/about</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of female governors in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal box|Rhode Island}}\n* [http://www.governor.ri.gov/ Rhode Island Governor Gina Raimondo] official government site\n* [https://ginaraimondo.com Gina Raimondo for Governor] official campaign site\n*{{Curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/Rhode_Island/Government/Executive/Governor_Gina_Raimondo}}\n*{{C-SPAN|ginaraimondo}}\n*[https://sosri.access.preservica.com/uncategorized/digitalFile_2f7f2f64-4c2e-48c2-8e35-658c6dfcee75/ Governor Gina M. Raimondo Inauguration Program] from the Rhode Island State Archives\n\n{{commons category|Gina Raimondo}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Frank T. Caprio|Frank Caprio]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[List of Governors of Rhode Island|Governor of Rhode Island]]|years=[[Rhode Island gubernatorial election, 2014|2014]], [[Rhode Island gubernatorial election, 2018|2018]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jay Inslee]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Phil Murphy]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lincoln Chafee]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Governors of Rhode Island|Governor of Rhode Island]]|years=2015\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Mike Pence]]|as=[[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]]}}\n{{s-ttl|rows=2|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Within Rhode Island}}\n{{s-aft|after=Mayor of city<br>in which event is held}}\n|-\n{{s-aft|after=Otherwise {{Incumbent U.S. House Speaker}}<br>{{nowrap|''as [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives]]''}}}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Roy Cooper]]|as=[[List of Governors of North Carolina|Governor of North Carolina]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Outside Rhode Island}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Phil Scott (politician)|Phil Scott]]|as=[[List of Governors of Vermont|Governor of Vermont]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of Rhode Island}} \n{{Current U.S. governors}}\n{{Private equity investors}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raimondo, Gina}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of New College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American business executives]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:American venture capitalists]]\n[[Category:American women business executives]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Governors of Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Harvard Crimson alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:La Salle Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Smithfield, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island Democrats]]\n[[Category:State treasurers of Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Women in Rhode Island politics]]\n[[Category:Women state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Yale Law School alumni]]\n", "name_user": "74.103.255.50", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gina_Raimondo"}
{"title_page": "Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath", "text_new": "{{short description|English politician, artist and author}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Most Honourable]]\n| name = Alexander Thynn\n| honorific-suffix = \n| birthname = Alexander George Thynne\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1932|5|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[London]], England\n| death_date = {{death-date and age|4 April 2020|6 May 1932}}\n| death_place = [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], England\n| alma_mater = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Eton College]]\n*[[Christ Church, Oxford]]}}\n| occupation = Politician, artist, author\n| office = [[Marquess of Bath]]\n| term_start = 30 June 1992\n| term_end = 4 April 2020\n| predecessor = [[Henry Thynne, 6th Marquess of Bath|Henry Thynne]]\n| successor = [[Ceawlin Thynn, 8th Marquess of Bath|Ceawlin Thynn]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Anna Thynn, Marchioness of Bath|Anna Gyarmathy]]|1969}}\n| children = {{Plainlist|\n*Lady Lenka Thynn\n*[[Ceawlin Thynn, 8th Marquess of Bath]]}}\n| parents = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Henry Thynne, 6th Marquess of Bath]]\n*[[Daphne Fielding]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Alexander George Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath''' (6 May 1932 \u2013 4 April 2020), styled '''Viscount Weymouth''' between 1946 and 1992, was an English politician, artist, and author. He was ranked 359th in the ''[[Sunday Times Rich List 2009]]'' with an estimated wealth of \u00a3157&nbsp;million.\n\n==Early life and education==\nThynn was born in [[London]], the son of [[Henry Thynne, 6th Marquess of Bath]] and [[Daphne Fielding]], and grew up at his family's seat, [[Longleat]], a great [[Elizabethan]] house set in Wiltshire parkland landscaped in the 18th century by [[Capability Brown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.longleat.co.uk/longleat-house/formal-gardens|title=Formal Gardens|publisher=Longleat (official website)|accessdate=15 September 2017}}</ref> After attending [[Ludgrove School]] and [[Eton College]], he was commissioned into the [[Life Guards (British Army)|Life Guards]] as a [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] in 1951.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/3299181/Loveless-lord-of-Longleat.html|title=Loveless lord of Longleat|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=20 November 2002|accessdate=15 September 2017}}</ref> He was then educated at [[Christ Church, Oxford]], where he was president of the [[Bullingdon Club]], and travelled across [[Europe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/news/riot-club-film-bullingdon-oxford-university-boris-cameron |title=Oxford\u2019s Bullingdon boys: in a class of their own \u2013 Channel 4 News |website=Channel4.com |date=12 September 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nBelieving that [[Wessex]] would be better off as a devolved region within the UK, he stood in the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February 1974 General Election]] as a Wessex regionalist. Shortly after the election, he was one of the founders of the [[Wessex Regionalist Party]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Petridis |first1=Alexis |title=Cider, morris dancing and 100% tax: an election strategy with a difference |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/may/03/cider-morris-dancing-election-wessex |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=3 May 2010}}</ref> He stood for the party in the first ever elections to the [[European Parliament]] in [[1979 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|1979]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fort |first1=Linda |title=Wessex Regionalists want \"devo-opt\" for Berkshire and points west |url=https://www.getreading.co.uk/news/reading-berkshire-news/wessex-regionalists-want-devo-opt-berkshire-8962007 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=BerkshireLive |date=2 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter inheriting the [[Marquess of Bath|marquessate]] from his father in 1992, he sat in the [[House of Lords]] as a [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]]. Among other things, he spoke on the need for devolution for the regions of England, until he lost his place in the House of Lords after the [[The Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Government's reforms excluded most of the hereditary [[peerage|peers]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Savill |first1=Richard |title=Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath: profile |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/7428850/Alexander-Thynn-7th-Marquess-of-Bath-profile.html |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=12 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Bath, marquess of.svg|thumb|upright|Arms of the marquesses of Bath: ''Quarterly: 1st and 4th, Barry of ten Or and Sable (Botteville); 2nd and 3rd, Argent, a Lion rampant with tail nowed and erect Gules (Thynne)'']]\nIn 1969, Thynn married Hungarian-born [[Anna Thynn, Marchioness of Bath|Anna Gyarmathy]], also known as Anna Gael,<ref name=\"Bradreth\">[[Gyles Brandreth]], \n[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/3299181/Loveless-lord-of-Longleat.html \"Loveless lord of Longleat\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 20 November 2002</ref> by whom he had two children, Lady Lenka Abigail Thynn and [[Ceawlin Thynn, 8th Marquess of Bath]], who were sent to the local comprehensive school.<ref name=\"Cooke\">Cooke, Rachel (10 March 2002). [https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2002/mar/10/features.review17 \"The loins of Longleat\"], ''The Observer''. Retrieved 5 April 2020.</ref> Lord Bath  also acknowledged an illegitimate daughter born circa 2000.<ref>{{cite news|author=Douglas, Alice |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2010/jan/30/marquess-bath-family-values |title=Marquess of Bath: My family values &#124; Life and style |work=[[The Guardian]] |date= 30 January 2010|accessdate= 5 April 2020}}</ref> He had open sexual relations with over seventy women during his marriage, and installed many in estate cottages. He referred to these women as ''wifelets''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bates |first1=Stephen |title=The Marquess of Bath obituary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/apr/05/the-marquess-of-bath-obituary |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Orr |first1=James |title='Wifelets' fight over affections of Lord Bath |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/wifelets-fight-over-affections-of-lord-bath-2296126.html |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=Independent |date=11 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Guise |first1=Richard |title=A Wiggly Way Through England |date=2013 |publisher=Lulu.com |isbn=9780954558741 |page=71 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=c7GgBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA71&lpg=PA71&dq=wifelets+marquess+bath&source=bl&ots=7AjF2qk6aX&sig=ACfU3U0YFA44Ga6uloMNiXU4drq-VoHRPw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiW7Nu1_tPoAhWVFMAKHb_jD7E4HhDoATAGegQIDBAo#v=onepage&q=wifelets%20marquess%20bath&f=false |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Le Vay |first1=Benedict |title=Eccentric Britain |date=2005 |publisher=Bradt Travel Guides |isbn=9781841621227 |page=108 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NDtK62KVHtQC&pg=PA108&dq=wifelets+marquess+bath&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiV_YXm_9PoAhUhpnEKHUevBPcQ6AEIPjAD#v=onepage&q=wifelets%20marquess%20bath&f=false |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Lisners |first1=John |title=The Rise and Fall of the Murdoch Empire |date=2012 |publisher=Kings Road Publishing |isbn=9781857827439 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ySGtDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT147&dq=wifelets+marquess+bath&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiV_YXm_9PoAhUhpnEKHUevBPcQ6AEIcTAJ#v=onepage&q=wifelets%20marquess%20bath&f=false |accessdate=6 April 2020 |format=Ebook}}</ref>\n\nBorn with the family name Thynne, he dropped the \"e\" in 1976, as he wanted to emphasise its correct pronunciation to rhyme with \"pin\" and not \"pine\". He was known for his colourful style of dress, which he acquired as an art student in Paris in the 1950s,<ref>Savill, Richard (12 March 2010). [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/7428850/Alexander-Thynn-7th-Marquess-of-Bath-profile.html \"Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath: profile\"], ''The Daily Telegraph''. Retrieved 5 April 2020.</ref> and was a prolific amateur painter who decorated rooms of his home with erotic scenes from the ''[[Kama Sutra]]''.<ref name=\"Bradreth\"/><ref name=\"Cooke\"/>\n\nAfter his father's death in 1992, he dismissed his younger brother Christopher as estate controller and evicted him from his home on the Longleat estate.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/marquess-of-bath-evicts-younger-brother-1557256.html \"Marquess of Bath evicts younger brother\"], ''The Independent'', 14 October 1992</ref> In early 2010, he passed the management of the business to his son, Viscount Weymouth.<ref>Simon de Bruxelles [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article7060610.ece \"Lord Bath announces retirement from Longleat safari park business\"], ''The Times'', 13 March 2010</ref> By one account, the Viscount intended to evict the mistresses from their estate cottages.<ref>Wyn Ellis, p.189</ref>  Some of his father's murals were removed, which caused a rift and led to a boycott by the Marquess of his son's marriage to [[Emma Thynn, Viscountess Weymouth|Emma McQuiston]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/mother-tongue/familyhistory/10849257/Viscountess-puts-wedding-on-display-after-father-in-law-Lord-Bath-snubbed-big-day.html |title=Viscountess puts wedding on display after father-in-law Lord Bath snubbed big day |author= Carter, Claire|date= 22 May 2014|access-date= 5 April 2020|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref>\n\nHe was admitted to the [[Royal United Hospital]], Bath, on 28 March 2020, and while in hospital tested positive for [[COVID-19]] during the [[2019-2020 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]]. He died of the disease on 4 April 2020 at the age of 87.<ref name=\"BBC-52173794\">{{cite web |title=Lord Bath dies after contracting coronavirus |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-52173794 |website=BBC News |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The 7th Marquess of Bath, Britain's most flamboyant and eccentric aristocrat \u2013 obituary|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/obituaries/2020/04/05/7th-marquess-bath-britains-flamboyant-eccentric-aristocrat/ |work=The Sunday Telegraph |date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Lord Bath dies aged 87 after contracting coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/apr/05/lord-bath-longleat-dies-contracting-covid-19-coronavirus-marquess |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=David |title=Marquess of Bath, bus drivers and a Dam Buster are coronavirus victims |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/marquess-of-bath-bus-drivers-and-a-dam-buster-are-coronavirus-victims-kmbf6t2kd |work=The Times |date=5 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Appearances and media==\nIn 1999 Thynn appeared in series 6, episode 4 of ''[[Time Team]]'', which dealt with the excavation of a cave in the [[Cheddar Gorge]], an area of land owned by him.<ref>{{cite web |title=Time Team: Time Team - On Demand |url=https://www.channel4.com/programmes/time-team/on-demand/25721-004 |website=Channel 4 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> From 2000 to 2009 ''[[Animal Park]]'', a television documentary about the life of keepers and animals at [[Longleat Safari Park]], Wiltshire, England, aired over 9 series on the BBC.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Quinn |first1=Ben |title=Longleat lions destroyed after rise in pregnancies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/feb/09/longleat-safari-park-lions-destroyed |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=9 February 2014}}</ref> It also covered the daily life of workers in Longleat House, the estate and the gardens and regularly featured items about Lord Bath himself.\n\nIn March 2009, he appeared in episode 4 of ''[[Heston's Feasts]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Roman {{!}} Episode 5 {{!}} Season 1 {{!}} Heston's Feasts on SBS |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/shows/hestonsfeasts/episodes/detail/episode/2317/season/1 |website=www.sbs.com.au |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> ''The Marquess of Bath'', a book by [[Nesta Wyn Ellis]], initially written with Bath's co-operation, was published in the autumn of 2010.<ref>Richard Eden [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/7920411/Libidinous-Lord-Bath-is-brought-to-book.html \"Libidinous Lord Bath is brought to book \"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 1 August 2010</ref> Lord Bath's autobiography, collectively called ''Strictly Private to Public Exposure'',<ref>{{cite news |title=Lord Bath reveals his life secrets |url=https://www.gazetteandherald.co.uk/news/7333024.lord-bath-reveals-his-life-secrets/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Wiltshire Gazette and Herald |date=29 November 2002 |language=en}}</ref> was first published as a series by Artnik Books, and since 2002 has been republished by Top Spot Publishing. His other screen credits include an episode of ''[[Globe Trekker]]''. He played an aristocrat in the music video for the [[Pet Shop Boys]] song [[Rent (song)|''Rent'']].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Burke |first1=David |title=The Lowdown: Pet Shop Boys |url=https://www.classicpopmag.com/2018/11/the-lowdown-pet-shop-boys/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Classic Pop Magazine |date=27 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nArtist and potter [[Grayson Perry]] interviewed the Marquess in the third of his three-part 2012 documentary series ''All in the Best Possible Taste with Grayson Perry'' which focused on Britain's upper class.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Graham |first1=Alison |title=All in the Best Possible Taste with Grayson Perry - S1 - Episode 3 |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/tv-programme/e/q466d/all-in-the-best-possible-taste-with-grayson-perry--s1-e3-all-in-the-best-possible-taste-with-grayson-perry/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Radio Times |language=en}}</ref> In 2014 Thynn appeared in ''All Change at Longleat'', a three-part documentary of some of the issues as he passed the running of the house to his son.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mount |first1=Harry |title=All Change at Longleat, review: 'dull without the Marquess in charge' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/11864997/All-Change-at-Longleat-review.html |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=14 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{Cite book|title=The New World Order of Alexander Thynn: Views on Politics, Society and Religion by the Marquess of Bath|year=2000|author=Bath, Alexander Thynn |location=London|publisher=Starhaven|isbn=0-936315-13-X}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Strictly Private to Public Exposure (Series 1: A Plateful of Privilege)|year=2002|author=Bath, Alexander Thynn |location=London|publisher=Artnik|isbn=978-1-903906-08-8}}\n*{{Cite book|title=The Marquess of Bath|year=2010|author=Ellis, Nesta |authorlink=Nesta Wyn Ellis|location=London|publisher=Dynasty Press|isbn=978-0-9553507-4-0}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.lordbath.co.uk/}}\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-alexander-thynn | the Marquess of Bath }}\n*[http://www.thepeerage.com/p2407.htm#i24064 Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|gb}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Henry Thynne, 6th Marquess of Bath|Henry Thynne]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Marquess of Bath]]\n | years  = 1992\u20132020 \n}}\n{{s-aft| after=[[Ceawlin Thynn, Viscount Weymouth|Ceawlin Thynn]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Thynne family tree}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bath, Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess Of}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ Church, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British Life Guards officers]]\n[[Category:British writers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) hereditary peers]]\n[[Category:Marquesses of Bath|Alexander]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ludgrove School]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English politician, artist and author}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Most Honourable]]\n| name = Alexander Thynn\n| honorific-suffix = \n| birthname = Alexander George Thynne\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1932|5|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[London]], England\n| death_date = {{death-date and age|4 April 2020|6 May 1932}}\n| death_place = [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], England\n| alma_mater = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Eton College]]\n*[[Christ Church, Oxford]]}}\n| occupation = Politician, artist, author\n| office = [[Marquess of Bath]]\n| term_start = 30 June 1992\n| term_end = 4 April 2020\n| predecessor = [[Henry Thynne, 6th Marquess of Bath|Henry Thynne]]\n| successor = [[Ceawlin Thynn, 8th Marquess of Bath|Ceawlin Thynn]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Anna Thynn, Marchioness of Bath|Anna Gyarmathy]]|1969}}\n| children = {{Plainlist|\n*Lady Lenka Thynn\n*[[Ceawlin Thynn, 8th Marquess of Bath]]}}\n| parents = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Henry Thynne, 6th Marquess of Bath]]\n*[[Daphne Fielding]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Alexander George Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath''' (6 May 1932 \u2013 4 April 2020), styled '''Viscount Weymouth''' between 1946 and 1992, was an English politician, artist, and author. He was ranked 359th in the ''[[Sunday Times Rich List 2009]]'' with an estimated wealth of \u00a3157&nbsp;million.\n\n==Early life and education==\nThynn was born in [[London]], the son of [[Henry Thynne, 6th Marquess of Bath]] and [[Daphne Fielding]], and grew up at his family's seat, [[Longleat]], a great [[Elizabethan]] house set in Wiltshire parkland landscaped in the 18th century by [[Capability Brown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.longleat.co.uk/longleat-house/formal-gardens|title=Formal Gardens|publisher=Longleat (official website)|accessdate=15 September 2017}}</ref> After attending [[Ludgrove School]] and [[Eton College]], he was commissioned into the [[Life Guards (British Army)|Life Guards]] as a [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] in 1951.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/3299181/Loveless-lord-of-Longleat.html|title=Loveless lord of Longleat|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=20 November 2002|accessdate=15 September 2017}}</ref> He was then educated at [[Christ Church, Oxford]], where he was president of the [[Bullingdon Club]], and travelled across [[Europe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/news/riot-club-film-bullingdon-oxford-university-boris-cameron |title=Oxford\u2019s Bullingdon boys: in a class of their own \u2013 Channel 4 News |website=Channel4.com |date=2014-09-12 |accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nBelieving that [[Wessex]] would be better off as a devolved region within the UK, he stood in the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February 1974 General Election]] as a Wessex regionalist. Shortly after the election, he was one of the founders of the [[Wessex Regionalist Party]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Petridis |first1=Alexis |title=Cider, morris dancing and 100% tax: an election strategy with a difference |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/may/03/cider-morris-dancing-election-wessex |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=3 May 2010}}</ref> He stood for the party in the first ever elections to the [[European Parliament]] in [[1979 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|1979]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fort |first1=Linda |title=Wessex Regionalists want \"devo-opt\" for Berkshire and points west |url=https://www.getreading.co.uk/news/reading-berkshire-news/wessex-regionalists-want-devo-opt-berkshire-8962007 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=BerkshireLive |date=2 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter inheriting the [[Marquess of Bath|marquessate]] from his father in 1992, he sat in the [[House of Lords]] as a [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]]. Among other things, he spoke on the need for devolution for the regions of England, until he lost his place in the House of Lords after the [[The Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Government's reforms excluded most of the hereditary [[peerage|peers]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Savill |first1=Richard |title=Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath: profile |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/7428850/Alexander-Thynn-7th-Marquess-of-Bath-profile.html |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=12 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Bath, marquess of.svg|thumb|upright|Arms of the marquesses of Bath: ''Quarterly: 1st and 4th, Barry of ten Or and Sable (Botteville); 2nd and 3rd, Argent, a Lion rampant with tail nowed and erect Gules (Thynne)'']]\nIn 1969, Thynn married Hungarian-born [[Anna Thynn, Marchioness of Bath|Anna Gyarmathy]], also known as Anna Gael,<ref name=\"Bradreth\">[[Gyles Brandreth]], \n[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/3299181/Loveless-lord-of-Longleat.html \"Loveless lord of Longleat\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 20 November 2002</ref> by whom he had two children, Lady Lenka Abigail Thynn and [[Ceawlin Thynn, 8th Marquess of Bath]], who were sent to the local comprehensive school.<ref name=\"Cooke\">Cooke, Rachel (10 March 2002). [https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2002/mar/10/features.review17 \"The loins of Longleat\"], ''The Observer''. Retrieved 5 April 2020.</ref> Lord Bath  also acknowledged an illegitimate daughter born circa 2000.<ref>{{cite news|author=Douglas, Alice |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2010/jan/30/marquess-bath-family-values |title=Marquess of Bath: My family values &#124; Life and style |work=[[The Guardian]] |date= 30 January 2010|accessdate= 5 April 2020}}</ref> He had open sexual relations with over seventy women during his marriage, and installed many in estate cottages. He referred to these women as ''wifelets''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bates |first1=Stephen |title=The Marquess of Bath obituary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/apr/05/the-marquess-of-bath-obituary |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Orr |first1=James |title='Wifelets' fight over affections of Lord Bath |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/wifelets-fight-over-affections-of-lord-bath-2296126.html |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=Independent |date=11 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Guise |first1=Richard |title=A Wiggly Way Through England |date=2013 |publisher=Lulu.com |isbn=9780954558741 |page=71 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=c7GgBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA71&lpg=PA71&dq=wifelets+marquess+bath&source=bl&ots=7AjF2qk6aX&sig=ACfU3U0YFA44Ga6uloMNiXU4drq-VoHRPw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiW7Nu1_tPoAhWVFMAKHb_jD7E4HhDoATAGegQIDBAo#v=onepage&q=wifelets%20marquess%20bath&f=false |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Le Vay |first1=Benedict |title=Eccentric Britain |date=2005 |publisher=Bradt Travel Guides |isbn=9781841621227 |page=108 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NDtK62KVHtQC&pg=PA108&dq=wifelets+marquess+bath&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiV_YXm_9PoAhUhpnEKHUevBPcQ6AEIPjAD#v=onepage&q=wifelets%20marquess%20bath&f=false |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Lisners |first1=John |title=The Rise and Fall of the Murdoch Empire |date=2012 |publisher=Kings Road Publishing |isbn=9781857827439 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ySGtDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT147&dq=wifelets+marquess+bath&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiV_YXm_9PoAhUhpnEKHUevBPcQ6AEIcTAJ#v=onepage&q=wifelets%20marquess%20bath&f=false |accessdate=6 April 2020 |format=Ebook}}</ref>\n\nBorn with the family name Thynne, he dropped the \"e\" in 1976, as he wanted to emphasise its correct pronunciation to rhyme with \"pin\" and not \"pine\". He was known for his colourful style of dress, which he acquired as an art student in Paris in the 1950s,<ref>Savill, Richard (12 March 2010). [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/7428850/Alexander-Thynn-7th-Marquess-of-Bath-profile.html \"Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath: profile\"], ''The Daily Telegraph''. Retrieved 5 April 2020.</ref> and was a prolific amateur painter who decorated rooms of his home with erotic scenes from the ''[[Kama Sutra]]''.<ref name=\"Bradreth\"/><ref name=\"Cooke\"/>\n\nAfter his father's death in 1992, he dismissed his younger brother Christopher as estate controller and evicted him from his home on the Longleat estate.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/marquess-of-bath-evicts-younger-brother-1557256.html \"Marquess of Bath evicts younger brother\"], ''The Independent'', 14 October 1992</ref> In early 2010, he passed the management of the business to his son, Viscount Weymouth.<ref>Simon de Bruxelles [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article7060610.ece \"Lord Bath announces retirement from Longleat safari park business\"], ''The Times'', 13 March 2010</ref> By one account, the Viscount intended to evict the mistresses from their estate cottages.<ref>Wyn Ellis, p.189</ref>  Some of his father's murals were removed, which caused a rift and led to a boycott by the Marquess of his son's marriage to [[Emma Thynn, Viscountess Weymouth|Emma McQuiston]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/mother-tongue/familyhistory/10849257/Viscountess-puts-wedding-on-display-after-father-in-law-Lord-Bath-snubbed-big-day.html |title=Viscountess puts wedding on display after father-in-law Lord Bath snubbed big day |author= Carter, Claire|date= 22 May 2014|access-date= 5 April 2020|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref>\n\nHe was admitted to the [[Royal United Hospital]], Bath, on 28 March 2020, and while in hospital tested positive for [[COVID-19]] during the [[2019-2020 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]]. He died of the disease on 4 April 2020 at the age of 87.<ref name=\"BBC-52173794\">{{cite web |title=Lord Bath dies after contracting coronavirus |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-52173794 |website=BBC News |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The 7th Marquess of Bath, Britain's most flamboyant and eccentric aristocrat \u2013 obituary|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/obituaries/2020/04/05/7th-marquess-bath-britains-flamboyant-eccentric-aristocrat/ |work=The Sunday Telegraph |date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Lord Bath dies aged 87 after contracting coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/apr/05/lord-bath-longleat-dies-contracting-covid-19-coronavirus-marquess |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=David |title=Marquess of Bath, bus drivers and a Dam Buster are coronavirus victims |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/marquess-of-bath-bus-drivers-and-a-dam-buster-are-coronavirus-victims-kmbf6t2kd |work=The Times |date=5 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Appearances and media==\nIn 1999 Thynn appeared in series 6, episode 4 of ''[[Time Team]]'', which dealt with the excavation of a cave in the [[Cheddar Gorge]], an area of land owned by him.<ref>{{cite web |title=Time Team: Time Team - On Demand |url=https://www.channel4.com/programmes/time-team/on-demand/25721-004 |website=Channel 4 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> From 2000 to 2009 ''[[Animal Park]]'', a television documentary about the life of keepers and animals at [[Longleat Safari Park]], Wiltshire, England, aired over 9 series on the BBC.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Quinn |first1=Ben |title=Longleat lions destroyed after rise in pregnancies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/feb/09/longleat-safari-park-lions-destroyed |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=9 February 2014}}</ref> It also covered the daily life of workers in Longleat House, the estate and the gardens and regularly featured items about Lord Bath himself.\n\nIn March 2009, he appeared in episode 4 of ''[[Heston's Feasts]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Roman {{!}} Episode 5 {{!}} Season 1 {{!}} Heston's Feasts on SBS |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/shows/hestonsfeasts/episodes/detail/episode/2317/season/1 |website=www.sbs.com.au |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> ''The Marquess of Bath'', a book by [[Nesta Wyn Ellis]], initially written with Bath's co-operation, was published in the autumn of 2010.<ref>Richard Eden [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/7920411/Libidinous-Lord-Bath-is-brought-to-book.html \"Libidinous Lord Bath is brought to book \"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 1 August 2010</ref> Lord Bath's autobiography, collectively called ''Strictly Private to Public Exposure'',<ref>{{cite news |title=Lord Bath reveals his life secrets |url=https://www.gazetteandherald.co.uk/news/7333024.lord-bath-reveals-his-life-secrets/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Wiltshire Gazette and Herald |date=29 November 2002 |language=en}}</ref> was first published as a series by Artnik Books, and since 2002 has been republished by Top Spot Publishing. His other screen credits include an episode of ''[[Globe Trekker]]''. He played an aristocrat in the music video for the [[Pet Shop Boys]] song [[Rent (song)|''Rent'']].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Burke |first1=David |title=The Lowdown: Pet Shop Boys |url=https://www.classicpopmag.com/2018/11/the-lowdown-pet-shop-boys/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Classic Pop Magazine |date=27 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nArtist and potter [[Grayson Perry]] interviewed the Marquess in the third of his three-part 2012 documentary series ''All in the Best Possible Taste with Grayson Perry'' which focused on Britain's upper class.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Graham |first1=Alison |title=All in the Best Possible Taste with Grayson Perry - S1 - Episode 3 |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/tv-programme/e/q466d/all-in-the-best-possible-taste-with-grayson-perry--s1-e3-all-in-the-best-possible-taste-with-grayson-perry/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Radio Times |language=en}}</ref> In 2014 Thynn appeared in ''All Change at Longleat'', a three-part documentary of some of the issues as he passed the running of the house to his son.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mount |first1=Harry |title=All Change at Longleat, review: 'dull without the Marquess in charge' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/11864997/All-Change-at-Longleat-review.html |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=14 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{Cite book|title=The New World Order of Alexander Thynn: Views on Politics, Society and Religion by the Marquess of Bath|year=2000|author=Bath, Alexander Thynn |location=London|publisher=Starhaven|isbn=0-936315-13-X}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Strictly Private to Public Exposure (Series 1: A Plateful of Privilege)|year=2002|author=Bath, Alexander Thynn |location=London|publisher=Artnik|isbn=978-1-903906-08-8}}\n*{{Cite book|title=The Marquess of Bath|year=2010|author=Ellis, Nesta |authorlink=Nesta Wyn Ellis|location=London|publisher=Dynasty Press|isbn=978-0-9553507-4-0}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.lordbath.co.uk/}}\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-alexander-thynn | the Marquess of Bath }}\n*[http://www.thepeerage.com/p2407.htm#i24064 Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess of Bath]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|gb}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Henry Thynne, 6th Marquess of Bath|Henry Thynne]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Marquess of Bath]]\n | years  = 1992\u20132020 \n}}\n{{s-aft| after=[[Ceawlin Thynn, Viscount Weymouth|Ceawlin Thynn]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Thynne family tree}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bath, Alexander Thynn, 7th Marquess Of}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ Church, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British Life Guards officers]]\n[[Category:British writers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) hereditary peers]]\n[[Category:Marquesses of Bath|Alexander]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ludgrove School]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_Thynn,_7th_Marquess_of_Bath"}
{"title_page": "Daniel James (footballer)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Daniel James\n| image          = Daniel James Wolves vs Man U 2020-01-04 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        = James playing for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in 2020\n| fullname       = Daniel Owen James<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/-/media/files/thefaportal/governance-docs/registrations/july-2017.ashx |title=List of Players under Written Contract Registered Between 01/07/2017 and 31/07/2017 |publisher=The Football Association |format=PDF |page=17 |accessdate=12 June 2019 }}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1997|11|10|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/13797/Daniel-James/overview |title=Daniel James: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=12 June 2019 }}</ref>\n| birth_place    = [[Kingston upon Hull]], England\n| height         = {{convert|1.70|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/players/daniel-james/316309/ |title=D. James: Summary |website=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |accessdate=12 June 2019 }}</ref>\n| position       = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]\n| currentclub    = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n| clubnumber     = 21\n| youthyears1    = 2006\u20132014 |youthclubs1 = [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]]\n| youthyears2    = 2014\u20132016 |youthclubs2 = [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]]\n| years1         = 2016\u20132019 |clubs1 = [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]]              |caps1 = 33 |goals1 = 4\n| years2         = 2017      |clubs2 = \u2192 [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] (loan) |caps2 = 0  |goals2 = 0\n| years3         = 2019\u2013     |clubs3 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]      |caps3 = 27 |goals3 = 3\n| nationalyears1 = 2013\u20132015 |nationalteam1 = [[Wales national under-17 football team|Wales U17]] |nationalcaps1 = 8  |nationalgoals1 = 2\n| nationalyears2 = 2015\u20132016 |nationalteam2 = [[Wales national under-19 football team|Wales U19]] |nationalcaps2 = 5  |nationalgoals2 = 1\n| nationalyears3 = 2017      |nationalteam3 = [[Wales national under-20 football team|Wales U20]] |nationalcaps3 = 3  |nationalgoals3 = 1\n| nationalyears4 = 2016\u20132018 |nationalteam4 = [[Wales national under-21 football team|Wales U21]] |nationalcaps4 = 11 |nationalgoals4 = 0\n| nationalyears5 = 2018\u2013     |nationalteam5 = [[Wales national football team|Wales]]              |nationalcaps5 = 10  |nationalgoals5 = 2\n| club-update    = 18:24, 8 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 21:31, 19 November 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Daniel Owen James''' (born 10 November 1997) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] for {{English football updater|ManchesU}} club [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and the [[Wales national football team|Wales national team]].\n\nHe made his professional debut for [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] in February 2018, and signed for Manchester United in June 2019. He made his senior Wales debut in November 2018, having previously represented the nation at various youth levels.\nJames is a really good football player\n\n==Early life==\nJames was born in [[Kingston upon Hull]], East Riding of Yorkshire, and attended [[South Hunsley School]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/former-hull-city-rookie-daniel-2110936 |title=Former Hull City rookie Daniel James in line for full international honours with Wales |first=Philip |last=Buckingham |website=Hull Live |publisher=Local World |date=15 October 2018 |accessdate=12 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Swansea City===\n====Youth and beginnings====\nA highly regarded prospect of the [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] academy side, James joined [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] in 2014 for an initial fee of \u00a372,000,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/highly-rated-hull-city-youngster-dan-james-8216/story-21286534-detail/story.html |title=Highly-rated Hull City youngster Dan James 'lost' to Swansea City for \u00a372,000 |newspaper=Hull Daily Mail |date=25 June 2014 |accessdate=9 June 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150416004129/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Highly-rated-Hull-City-youngster-Dan-James-8216/story-21286534-detail/story.html# |archivedate=16 April 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref> immediately becoming part of their U18 academy side. By the 2016\u201317 season, James had become an integral part of the Swansea U23 side who gained promotion to the PDL Division 1, winning the league by an 11-point margin. Additionally, James contributed to the side winning the Premier League Cup, and reaching the semi-finals of the Premier League International Cup and the quarter-finals of the [[EFL Trophy]].\n\nFollowing his impressive displays in the development squad,<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.swanseacity.com/teams/swansea-city/daniel-james |title=Daniel James |publisher=Swansea City A.F.C. |website= |access-date=13 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510165348/https://www.swanseacity.com/teams/swansea-city/daniel-james |archive-date=10 May 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> James was included in the first-team squad for the first time in January 2016 for the FA Cup defeat to [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Higginson |first1=Marc |title=Oxford United 3\u20132 Swansea City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35216450 |accessdate=7 February 2018 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=10 January 2016}}</ref> Although James did not make an appearance off the bench, his progress was deemed sufficient for him to be offered a new three-year contract the following week.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.swanseacity.net/news/article/swansea-city-under-21s-keston-davies-daniel-james-new-contracts-2958209.aspx |title=Swans U21s' Keston Davies and Daniel James sign new contracts |publisher=Swansea City AFC |accessdate=9 June 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170528115017/http://www.swanseacity.net/news/article/swansea-city-under-21s-keston-davies-daniel-james-new-contracts-2958209.aspx# |archivedate=28 May 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref> He was again named on the bench for a [[Premier League]] fixture against [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] in October 2016.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/who-daniel-james-what-you-12108205 |title=Who is Daniel James? What you need to know about the exciting Swansea City teenager who made the bench at Stoke City |first=Dominic |last=Booth |date=1 November 2016 |website=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 June 2017, James signed for [[EFL League One|League One]] club [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] on loan until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40457596 |title=Daniel James: Swansea City winger joins Shrewsbury Town on season-long loan |publisher=BBC Sport |date=30 June 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref> His loan deal was terminated by mutual consent on 31 August 2017, after he failed to force his way into the starting 11.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.shrewsburytown.com/news/2017/august/dan-james-returns-to-swansea/ |title=Dan James returns to Swansea |publisher=Shrewsbury Town FC }}</ref> James' only inclusion in a matchday squad was as an unused substitute in an [[EFL Cup]] first round tie against [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40785845 |title=Nottingham Forest 2-1 Shrewsbury Town |date=8 August 2017 |accessdate=2 September 2019 |website=bbc.co.uk |publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\n====First team breakthrough====\nOn 6 February 2018, he made his Swansea first-team debut as a late substitute, scoring in the 82nd minute of an 8\u20131 FA Cup victory over [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pritchard |first1=Dafydd |title=Swansea City 8\u20131 Notts County |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42868353 |accessdate=7 February 2018 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe made his league debut for Swansea on 17 August 2018 in a 0\u20130 draw against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] in the [[EFL Championship]].<ref name=\"auto2\"/> He scored his first league goal for the club on 24 November 2018 in a 4\u20131 home defeat against [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=89708 |title=Daniel James |website=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm}}</ref> In December 2018, with James now a regular and one of the standout performers for Swansea,<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/heartwarming-moment-swansea-city-star-15371623 |title=The heartwarming moment Swansea City star Daniel James is given an early birthday surpriseCity |first=Tom |last=Coleman |date=4 November 2018 |website=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales}}</ref> manager [[Graham Potter]] revealed that the club were looking to open talks with James over a new contract.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46642860 |title=Daniel James: Swansea City open to talks with Wales winger over new deal |date=21 December 2018 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Despite discussion of a move to [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] during the January 2019 [[transfer window]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46937954 |title=Daniel James: Leeds United link 'just rumours' says Swansea City winger |date=20 January 2019 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-s-fight-to-sign-daniel-james-heading-for-the-wire-as-transfer-deadline-looms-1-9567028 |title=Leeds United's fight to sign Daniel James heading for the wire as transfer deadline looms |date=30 January 2019 |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post}}</ref> James was named in the starting line-up for Swansea against Birmingham City on 29 January, with James scoring his second goal of the season in a 3\u20133 draw.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46955103 |title=Swansea 3 Birmingham 3 |date=30 January 2019 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2019, with James expressing his desire to leave Swansea to join Leeds United, a structured \u00a310&nbsp;million fee was agreed between the two clubs, James agreed terms and completed the medical at Leeds,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/daniel-james-undergoing-leeds-united-medical-after-club-agree-deal-with-swansea-city-1-9568433 |title=Daniel James undergoing Leeds United medical after club agree deal with Swansea City |date=31 January 2019 |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post}}</ref> and was at [[Elland Road]] conducting signing interviews and announcement photoshoots ahead of the deal being completed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-deal-for-daniel-james-collapses-1-9569603 |title=Leeds United Deal for Dan James Collapses |date=31 January 2019 |newspaper=The Yorkshire Post}}</ref> However, after speculation of a disagreement between Swansea owners and their chairman regarding the structure of the deal an hour before the transfer window's 11&nbsp;pm deadline, James was left at Elland Road awaiting the deal to be signed off by Swansea, with the window closing at 11&nbsp;pm.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/02/01/leeds-furious-swansea-pull-plug-10m-daniel-james-deal-final/ |title=Leeds furious after Swansea pull plug on \u00a310m Daniel James deal in final minutes of deadline day |date=31 January 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nAfter Swansea failed to complete the deal, James' agent claimed it was \"very disappointing\" and claimed \"Swansea made no attempt to keep the player and at the first sign of money they couldn't show him the door quickly enough.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/news/agent-hits-out-very-disappointing-late-collapse-daniel-james-move-leeds |title=The agent of Swansea City winger Daniel James has revealed his disappointment at the final-hour collapse of his client's deadline day move to Leeds United |date=1 February 2019 |website=FourFourTwo |publisher=Future}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/what-leeds-united-swansea-city-15764765 |title=What Leeds United and Swansea City have said about Daniel James' failed move |date=1 February 2019 |website=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales}}</ref> At the end of the 2018\u201319 season, with Leeds missing out on automatic promotion, Leeds head coach [[Marcelo Bielsa]] said that he refused to blame the club for missing out on James, but said, \"I'm not underlying the importance of the absence of James\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/leeds-united-boss-marcelo-bieslas-16192389 |title=Leeds United boss Marcelo Bielsa's candid admission over botched move for Swansea City's Daniel James |date=28 April 2019 |website=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales}}</ref>\n\n===Manchester United===\nOn 6 June 2019, James underwent a medical with Premier League club [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] ahead of a transfer for a reported fee of \u00a315&nbsp;million with the potential for additional payments.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11667/11735920/daniel-james-completes-manchester-united-medical |title=Daniel James completes Manchester United medical |date=7 June 2019 |publisher=Sky Sports |accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> The following day, United announced they had agreed terms, \"in principle\", with Swansea for the signing of James.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/man-utd-agree-terms-for-daniel-james-transfer-from-swansea |title=Confirmed: Man Utd agree deal in principle to sign Daniel James |date=7 June 2019 |website=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> On 12 June 2019, United officially announced the signing of James on a five-year contract, with an option to extend for a further year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/daniel-james-completes-transfer-to-man-utd-subject-to-international-clearance|title=Welsh winger Daniel James seals transfer to Man Utd|website=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United }}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club on his competitive debut, coming on as a substitute to score United's final goal in a 4\u20130 win over [[Chelsea F.C|Chelsea]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2019/aug/11/manchester-united-v-chelsea-premier-league-live |title=Manchester United 4\u20130 Chelsea |date=11 August 2019 |website=theguardian.com |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=11 August 2019}}</ref> He also scored in United's 2\u20131 loss against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49378901|title=Manchester United 1\u20132 Crystal Palace |date=24 August 2019 |website=bbc.co.uk |publisher=BBC |accessdate=24 August 2019}}</ref> In only his fourth game for United he scored his third goal for the club in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49456551|title=Southampton 1\u20131 Manchester United |date=31 August 2019 |website=bbc.co.uk |publisher=BBC |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> which was later voted goal of the month by United fans.<ref>https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/daniel-james-wins-man-utd-august-2019-goal-of-the-month</ref> James was also voted United player of the month for August.<ref>https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/daniel-james-wins-first-player-of-the-month-award-of-the-season</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Youth levels===\nBorn in England, James qualifies to play for Wales through his late father, Kevan,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48379550 |title=Daniel James: Swansea winger withdraws from Wales camp after father's death |date=23 May 2019 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref> who was born in [[Aberdare]].<ref name=\"auto2\" /> James scored at the [[Toulon Tournament]] playing for [[Wales national under-20 football team|Wales U20]] in a 1\u20130 win over [[Bahrain national under-20 football team|Bahrain U20]] after he won and scored the resulting penalty.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/wales-under-20s-1-bahrain-13131188 |title=Wales in knock-out hunt after Bahrain victory |first=Andrew |last=Gwilym |date=2 June 2017 |website=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales}}</ref>\n\n===Senior team===\nJames received his first senior call-up for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] qualifying game against [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]] in 2017 by manager [[Chris Coleman (footballer)|Chris Coleman]]<ref name=\"auto2\"/> and subsequently made his full Wales debut under Coleman's successor, [[Ryan Giggs]], in a match against [[Albania national football team|Albania]] in November 2018, playing the first 58 minutes of the game.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swanseacity.com/news/dans-wales-pride |title=Dan's Wales pride |publisher=Swansea City A.F.C.}}</ref> James scored his first Wales goal in only his second cap, netting the only goal of the game in the opening minutes against [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]] in his competitive home debut.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/mar/24/wales-slovakia-euro-2020-qualifer-match-report |title=Wales up and running after Daniel James' early strike sinks Slovakia |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> During the September international break, James netted the only goal in a friendly win against [[Belarus national football team|Belarus]].<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/daniel-james-manchester-united-ryan-giggs-wales-belarus-euro-2020-a9098531.html%3famp</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nJames can play as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]], and also as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> He is known for his pace and skill.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 12 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[EFL Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Europe\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]]\n|[[2015\u201316 Swansea City A.F.C. season|2015\u201316]]<ref name=\"DJ15\">{{soccerbase season|89708|2015|accessdate=9 October 2017}}</ref>\n|[[Premier League]]\n|0||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 Swansea City A.F.C. season|2016\u201317]]<ref name=\"DJ16\">{{soccerbase season|89708|2016|accessdate=9 October 2017}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|0||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Swansea City A.F.C. season|2017\u201318]]<ref name=\"DJ17\">{{soccerbase season|89708|2017|accessdate=7 February 2018}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|0||0||1||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1||1\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Swansea City A.F.C. season|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"DJ18\">{{soccerbase season|89708|2018|accessdate=10 May 2019}}</ref>\n|[[EFL Championship|Championship]]\n|33||4||4||1||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"