es                 = \n| record_attendance      = \n| dimensions             = \n| field_shape            = \n| acreage                = \n| volume                 = \n| tenants                = \n| embedded               = \n| website                = \n| publictransit          = \n}} \nThe '''Spira Culture Center''' ({{lang-sv|Kulturhuset Spira}}) is a [[culture center]] in [[J\u00f6nk\u00f6ping]], [[Sweden]]. It was opened on 11 November 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jnytt.se/sa-blir-spiras-invigning|title=S\u00e5 blir Spiras invigning|publisher=J-nytt|language=Swedish|author=Peter Gustafsson|date=7 November 2011|accessdate=1 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402104452/http://www.jnytt.se/sa-blir-spiras-invigning|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat-inline|Spira Culture Center}}\n*[http://www.smot.se/ Spira] {{in lang|sv}}\n\n{{coord|57.7775|N|14.1717|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:2011 establishments in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in J\u00f6nk\u00f6ping]]\n[[Category:Music venues completed in 2011]]\n[[Category:Culture in J\u00f6nk\u00f6ping]]\n[[Category:Theatres completed in 2011]]\n", "name_user": "Stalverk80", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spira_Cultural_Center"}
{"title_page": "Tom Dempsey", "text_new": "{{short description|American football player}}\n{{other people}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name=Tom Dempsey\n|image=\n|number=19, 10, 23, 6\n|position=[[Placekicker]]\n|birth_date={{birth date|1947|1|12}}\n|birth_place=[[Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|2020|4|4|1947|1|12}}\n|death_place=[[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]]\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=2\n|weight_lbs=255\n|high_school=[[San Dieguito Academy|San Dieguito]]<br />([[Encinitas, California]])\n|college=[[Palomar College|Palomar]]\n|undraftedyear=1969\n|pastteams=\n* [[New Orleans Saints]] ({{NFL Year|1969}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1970}})\n* [[Philadelphia Eagles]] ({{NFL Year|1971}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1974}})\n* [[Los Angeles Rams]] ({{NFL Year|1975}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1976}})\n* [[Houston Oilers]] ({{NFL Year|1977}})\n* [[Buffalo Bills]] ({{NFL Year|1978}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1979}})\n|highlights=\n* [[Pro Bowl]] ([[1969 Pro Bowl|1969]])\n* First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[1969 All-Pro Team|1969]])\n* [[New Orleans Saints#New Orleans Saints Hall of Fame|New Orleans Saints Hall of Fame]]\n|statlabel1=[[conversion (gridiron football)|PAT]]\n|statvalue1=252/282 (89.4%)\n|statlabel2=[[Field goal (American and Canadian football)|FG]]\n|statvalue2=159/258 (61.6%)\n|nflnew=tomdempsey/2512783\n|pfr=D/DempTo20\n}}\n\n'''Thomas John Dempsey''' (January 12, 1947 \u2013 April 4, 2020) was an American professional [[American football|football]] player who was a [[placekicker]] in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) for the [[New Orleans Saints]], [[Philadelphia Eagles]], [[Los Angeles Rams]], [[Houston Oilers]] and [[Buffalo Bills]]. Unlike the \"soccer style\" approach which was becoming more and more widely used during his career, Dempsey's kicking style was the then-standard straight-toe style.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mitchell|first=Fred|title=IT'S A GAME OF INCHES . . . AND FEET|date=December 24, 1995|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|publisher=[[Tribune Publishing]]|location=[[Chicago]]|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1995-09-24-9509240039-story.html|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDempsey was born in [[Milwaukee]] and attended high school and college in Southern California. He attended high school at [[San Dieguito High School]] and played [[college football]] at [[Palomar College]]. He was born with no toes on his right foot and no fingers on his right hand. Dempsey wore a custom, flat-front kicking shoe that ended where his toes were supposed to begin.<ref name=\"McLaughlin\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/05/us/tom-dempsey-nfl-kicker-dies-coronavirus-trnd/index.html|title=Tom Dempsey, NFL kicker who set a record for the longest field goal, dies of coronavirus|first=Eliott C.|last=McLaughlin|work=[[CNN]]|publisher=[[WarnerMedia]]|location=[[Atlanta]]|date=April 5, 2020|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==NFL career==\nDempsey is most widely known for kicking a 63-yard [[Field goal (football)|field goal]] as time expired to give the Saints a 19\u201317 win over the [[Detroit Lions]] on November 8, 1970 at [[Tulane Stadium]] in [[New Orleans]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Rovin|first=Jeff|title=In Search of Trivia|publisher=[[Penguin Books]]|location=[[New York City]]|year=1984|edition=1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/insearchoftrivia00jeff/page/408 408]|isbn=978-0451162502|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/insearchoftrivia00jeff/page/408}}</ref> Prior to 1974, the goal posts in the NFL were on the goal lines instead of the end lines.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tainier|first=Mike|title=Manadatory Monday: Snow Mess|date=December 9, 2013|work=Sports On Earth|publisher=MLB Advanced Media, L.P.|location=United States|url=http://www.sportsonearth.com/article/64493936/|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> With time running out in the game, the Saints attempted a field goal with holder [[Joe Scarpati]] spotting at the Saints' own 37-yard line. The snap from [[Jackie Burkett]] was good, and Dempsey made the field goal as the ball fell just beyond the bar.<ref name=culpepper_12102013>{{cite news|last=Culpepper|first=Chuck|title=Still The One|date=December 10, 2013|work=Sports on Earth|url=http://www.sportsonearth.com/article/64526706|publisher=MLB Advanced Media, L.P.|location=United States|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> The win was one of only two for the Saints in that dismal season.<ref name=vargas_04042020>{{cite news|last=Vargas|first=Ramon Antonio|title=Tom Dempsey, historic New Orleans Saints placekicker, dies at 73 after coronavirus battle|date=April 4, 2020|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune/The New Orleans Advocate]]|publisher=Georges Media Group|location=[[New Orleans]]|url=https://www.nola.com/sports/saints/article_f4822bdf-7ef3-522e-8634-54ad5805dc21.html|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> \n\nWith the kick, Dempsey broke [[Bert Rechichar]]'s NFL record for longest field goal by seven yards. His record was tied three times\u2014by [[Jason Elam]] in 1998, [[Sebastian Janikowski]] in 2011 and [[David Akers]] in 2012<ref>{{cite news|last=Lewis|first=Ted|title=Denver kicker breaks Tom Dempsey\u2019s record with 64-yard field goal|date=December 8, 2013|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune/The New Orleans Advocate]]|publisher=Georges Media Group|location=[[New Orleans]]|url=https://www.nola.com/sports/article_10db0910-6987-5319-a780-12bb2c94a5b8.html|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\u2014before it was broken on December 8, 2013,\nby [[Matt Prater]] who hit a 64-yard field goal.<ref name=vargas_04042020/>  Dempsey's kick along with [[Graham Gano]]'s 63-yarder in 2018 are the longest field goals to win a game on its final play.<ref name=culpepper_12102013/>\n\n[[File:Tom dempsey.jpg|thumb|left|Dempsey's special kicking shoe]]\nDempsey was born without toes on his right foot and no fingers on his right hand. He wore a modified shoe with a flattened and enlarged toe surface. This generated controversy about whether such a shoe gave a player an unfair advantage.<ref name=daye_12022014>{{cite news|last=Daye|first=Raymond L.|date=December 2, 2014|title=Remembering \"The Kick\"|location=[[Marksville, Louisiana]]|publisher=Avoyelles Publishing Company|url=http://avoyellestoday.com/index.php/sports/1750-remembering-the-kick|work=[[Avoyelles Journal]]|publisher=Avoyelles Journal, Bunkie, Record, Marksville Weekly |accessdate=January 4, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104052651/http://avoyellestoday.com/index.php/sports/1750-remembering-the-kick|archivedate=January 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/28/sports/playmagazine/28lewis.html?pagewanted=8|title=The Kick Is Up and It's...A Career-Killer|work=[[The New York Times]]|first=Michael|last=Lewis|date=October 28, 2007|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|location=[[New York City]]accessdate=May 25, 2010}}</ref> When reporters would ask him if he thought it was unfair, he said, \"Unfair, eh? How 'bout you try kickin' a 63 yard field goal to win it with 2 seconds left an' yer wearin' a square shoe, oh yeah, and no toes either.\"<ref name=daye_12022014/> Additionally, when an analysis of his kick was carried out by [[ESPN]] ''[[Sport Science (TV series)|Sport Science]]'', it was found that his modified shoe had offered him no advantage. In fact, it was found that the smaller contact area could have reduced, not increased, the margin for error.<ref>{{cite web|title=World's Longest Field Goal|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uu7IqQNA6Ls|publisher=ESPN Sport's Science}}</ref>\n\nThe league made two rule changes in the subsequent years to discourage further long field goal attempts. The first was in 1974, which moved the goal posts from the goal line to the back of the end zone, adding ten yards to the kick distance, and awarded the ball to the defense on a missed kick at the spot where the ball was snapped. This was changed in 1994 to the spot of the kick. Then, in 1977, the [[1977 NFL season#Major rule changes|NFL added a rule]], informally known as the \"Tom Dempsey Rule\", that \"any shoe that is worn by a player with an artificial limb on his kicking leg must have a kicking surface that conforms to that of a normal kicking shoe.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballresearch.com/articles/frpage.cfm?topic=rulesname|title=Rules of the Name, or How the Emmitt Rule Became the Emmitt Rule,|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071211145916/http://www.footballresearch.com/articles/frpage.cfm?topic=rulesname|work=[[Professional Football Researchers Association]]|location=[[Grand Island, New York]]|publisher=PFRA, LLC|archivedate=December 11, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogmedia.thenewstribune.com/media/2006%20NFL%20RULEBOOK.pdf|title=Official NFL Rulebook 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100216075609/http://blogmedia.thenewstribune.com/media/2006%20NFL%20RULEBOOK.pdf|work=[[The News Tribune]]|publisher=[[McClatchy]]|location=[[Tacoma, Washington]]|archivedate=February 16, 2010}}See Rule 5, Section 3, Article 3 Paragraph (g)</ref>\n\n==Career regular season statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: auto; text-align: right; font-size: 90%; width: 800px;\"\n''Career high/best '''bold'''''\n|-\n! style=\"background:#DCDCDC;\" colspan=\"17\"| Regular season statistics\n|- style=\"font-size:x-small;\"\n!Season||Team (record)||{{abbr|G|Games}}||{{abbr|FGM|Field goals made}}||{{abbr|FGA|Field goals attempted}}||{{abbr|%|Field goal success percentage}}||{{abbr|<20|Field goals under 20 yards}}||{{abbr|20-29|Field goals between 20 and 29 yards}}||{{abbr|30-39|Field goals between 30 and 39 yards}}||{{abbr|40-49|Field goals between 40 and 49 yards}}||{{abbr|50+|Field goals 50 yards or over}}||{{abbr|LNG|Longest successful field goal}}||{{abbr|BLK|Field goal attempts blocked}}||{{abbr|XPM|Extra points made}}||{{abbr|XPA|Extra points attempted}}||{{abbr|%|Extra point success percentage}}||{{abbr|PTS|Points}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[1969 NFL season|1969]] ||style=\"text-align:left;\" nowrap=\"nowrap\"|[[New Orleans Saints]] ([[1969 New Orleans Saints season|5\u20139]])\n|14 ||22 ||'''41''' ||53.7 ||5\u20136 ||6\u20137 ||3\u20136 ||'''7\u201311''' ||1\u201311 ||55 ||0 ||33 ||35 ||94.3 ||99\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[1970 NFL season|1970]] ||style=\"text-align:left;\" nowrap=\"nowrap\"|[[New Orleans Saints]] ([[1970 New Orleans Saints season|2\u201311\u20131]])\n|14 ||18 ||34 ||52.9 ||4\u20135 ||6\u20138 ||1\u20135 ||4\u20137 ||3\u20139 ||'''63''' ||0 ||16 ||17 ||94.1 ||70\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[1971 NFL season|1971]] ||style=\"text-align:left;\" nowrap=\"nowrap\"|[[Philadelphia Eagles]] ([[1971 Philadelphia Eagles season|6\u20137\u20131]])\n|5 ||12 ||17 ||70.6 ||0\u20130 ||6\u20137 ||1\u20132 ||2\u20133 ||'''3\u20135''' ||54 ||0 ||13 ||14 ||92.9 ||49\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[1972 NFL season|1972]] ||style=\"text-align:left;\" nowrap=\"nowrap\"|[[Philadelphia Eagles]] ([[1972 Philadelphia Eagles season|2\u201311\u20131]])\n|14 ||20 ||35 ||57.1 ||6\u20136 ||3\u20136 ||'''7\u201310''' ||2\u20139 ||2\u20134 ||52 ||0 ||11 ||12 ||91.7 ||71\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[1973 NFL season|1973]] ||style=\"text-align:left;\" nowrap=\"nowrap\"|[[Philadelphia Eagles]] ([[1973 Philadelphia Eagles season|5\u20138\u20131]])\n|14 ||'''24''' ||40 ||60.0 ||'''7\u20137''' ||4\u20137 ||7\u201311 ||4\u20139 ||2\u20136 ||51 ||0 ||34 ||34 ||'''100.0''' ||'''106'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[1974 NFL season|1974]] ||style=\"text-align:left;\" nowrap=\"nowrap\"|[[Philadelphia Eagles]] ([[1974 Philadelphia Eagles season|7\u20137]])\n|14 ||10 ||16 ||62.5 ||1\u20131 ||1\u20132 ||4\u20136 ||4\u20136 ||0\u20131 ||48 ||0 ||26 ||30 ||86.7 ||56\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[1975 NFL season|1975]] ||style=\"text-align:left;\" nowrap=\"nowrap\"|[[Los Angeles Rams]] ([[1975 Los Angeles Rams season|12\u20132]])\n|14 ||21 ||26 ||'''80.8''' ||2\u20132 ||'''7\u20137''' ||'''7\u201310''' ||4\u20135 ||1\u20132 ||51 ||0 ||31 ||36 ||86.1 ||94\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[1976 NFL season|1976]] ||style=\"text-align:left;\" nowrap=\"nowrap\"|[[Los Angeles Rams]] ([[1976 Los Angeles Rams season|10\u20133\u20131]])\n|14 ||17 ||26 ||65.4 ||2\u20132 ||5\u20138 ||4\u20135 ||6\u201310 ||0\u20131 ||49 ||0 ||'''36''' ||'''44''' ||81.8 ||87\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[1977 NFL season|1977]] ||style=\"text-align:left;\" nowrap=\"nowrap\"|[[Houston Oilers]] ([[1977 Houston Oilers season|8\u20136]])\n|5 ||4 ||6 ||66.7 ||0\u20130 ||3\u20133 ||1\u20132 ||0\u20131 ||0\u20130 ||37 ||0 ||8 ||11 ||72.7 ||20\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[1978 NFL season|1978]] ||style=\"text-align:left;\" nowrap=\"nowrap\"|[[Buffalo Bills]] ([[1978 Buffalo Bills season|5\u201311]])\n|'''16''' ||10 ||13 ||76.9 ||0\u20130 ||5\u20135 ||4\u20135 ||1\u20133 ||0\u20130 ||46 ||0 ||'''36''' ||38 ||94.7 ||66\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[1979 NFL season|1979]] ||style=\"text-align:left;\" nowrap=\"nowrap\"|[[Buffalo Bills]] ([[1979 Buffalo Bills season|7\u20139]])\n|3 ||1 ||4 ||25.0 ||1\u20131 ||0\u20130 ||0\u20132 ||0\u20131 ||0\u20130 ||18 ||0 ||8 ||11 ||72.7 ||11\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Career (11 seasons) ||127 ||159 ||258 ||61.6 ||28\u201330 ||46\u201360 ||39\u201364 ||34\u201365 ||12\u201339 ||63 ||0 ||252 ||282 ||89.4 ||729\n|}\n\nSource:<ref>{{Cite pro-football-reference |name=Tom Dempsey|id=D/DempTo20|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Post career==\nIn 1983, Dempsey was inducted into the American Football Association's Semi-Pro Football Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ford|first=Mark L.|title=Semi-Pro Football Hall of Fame: The First 100 (or so) Members, 1981-1989|website=AmericanFootballAssn.com|url=https://www.americanfootballassn.com/forms/AFA-SPFHOF.pdf|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Poliquin|first=Bud|title=Pat Killorin, Syracuse's two-time All-American center, is a Semi-Pro Football Hall-of-Famer|date=July 27, 2004|website=Syracuse.com|url=https://www.syracuse.com/poliquin/2014/06/pat_killorin_syracuses_two-time_all-american_is_a_semi-pro_football_hall-of-fame.html|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{rquote|right|The hurricane flooded me out of a lot of memorabilia, but it can't flood out the memories.|Dempsey on the effects of [[Hurricane Katrina]]}}\nAfter retiring from football he resided with his wife Carlene, who taught history at Kehoe-France, a private school in [[Metairie, Louisiana]], a suburb of New Orleans.  His house was flooded during [[Hurricane Katrina]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/30/sports/football/30dempsey.html?8dpc|last=Crouse|first=Karen|title=A Favorite Saint|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|location=[[New York City]]|date=January 30, 2010|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Personal life and death==\nDempsey married Carlene and had three children with one named Ashley.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/sports/ex-nfl-kicker-saints-hero-tom-dempsey-dies-while-battling-n1177181|title=Ex-NFL kicker, Saints hero Tom Dempsey dies while battling coronavirus at 73|author=[[Associated Press]]|work=[[NBC News]]|publisher=[[NBC]]|location=[[New York City]]|date=April 5, 2020|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Dempsey revealed he was suffering from [[dementia]]. Psychiatrist [[Daniel Amen]] made the initial diagnosis of damage to Dempsey's brain. During medical examinations and scans, Amen found three holes in the brain, along with other damage.<ref>{{cite news|title= For former kicker, the price of fearlessness|first=Brett Michael|last=Dykes|date=January 27, 2013|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|location=[[New York City]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/28/sports/football/super-bowl-tom-dempsey-former-nfl-kicker-is-dealing-with-dementia.html|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, 2020, Dempsey tested positive for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Famed New Orleans Saints kicker Tom Dempsey has coronavirus|first=Mike|last=Triplett|date=March 30, 2020|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|location=[[Bristol, Connecticut]]|url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story?id=28971803&_slug_=famed-new-orleans-saints-kicker-tom-dempsey-coronavirus|access-date= March 31, 2020}}</ref> He was one of 15 residents at a [[New Orleans]] senior residence to test positive for the virus. Dempsey died on April 4, 2020 of complications of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Goldstein|first=Richard|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/05/obituaries/tom-dempsey-dead.html|title=Tom Dempsey, Record-Setting Kicker, Dies at 73|date=April 5, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 6, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Footballstats|nfl=2512783|pfr=D/DempTo20}}\n\n{{New Orleans Saints}}\n{{NFL on CBS}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dempsey, Tom}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American disabled sportspeople]]\n[[Category:American football placekickers]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bills players]]\n[[Category:Eastern Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Houston Oilers players]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Rams players]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Saints players]]\n[[Category:Palomar Comets football players]]\n[[Category:People from Metairie, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Eagles players]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Milwaukee]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Louisiana]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football player}}\n{{other people}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name=Tom Dempsey\n|image=\n|number=19, 10, 23, 6\n|position=[[Placekicker]]\n|birth_date={{birth date|1947|1|12}}\n|birth_place=[[Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|2020|4|4|1947|1|12}}\n|death_place=[[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]]\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=2\n|weight_lbs=255\n|high_school=[[San Dieguito Academy|San Dieguito]]<br />([[Encinitas, California]])\n|college=[[Palomar College|Palomar]]\n|undraftedyear=1969\n|pastteams=\n* [[New Orleans Saints]] ({{NFL Year|1969}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1970}})\n* [[Philadelphia Eagles]] ({{NFL Year|1971}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1974}})\n* [[Los Angeles Rams]] ({{NFL Year|1975}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1976}})\n* [[Houston Oilers]] ({{NFL Year|1977}})\n* [[Buffalo Bills]] ({{NFL Year|1978}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1979}})\n|highlights=\n* [[Pro Bowl]] ([[1969 Pro Bowl|1969]])\n* First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[1969 All-Pro Team|1969]])\n* [[New Orleans Saints#New Orleans Saints Hall of Fame|New Orleans Saints Hall of Fame]]\n|statlabel1=[[conversion (gridiron football)|PAT]]\n|statvalue1=252/282 (89.4%)\n|statlabel2=[[Field goal (American and Canadian football)|FG]]\n|statvalue2=159/258 (61.6%)\n|nflnew=tomdempsey/2512783\n|pfr=D/DempTo20\n}}\n\n'''Thomas John Dempsey''' (January 12, 1947 \u2013 April 4, 2020) was an American professional [[American football|football]] player who was a [[placekicker]] in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) for the [[New Orleans Saints]], [[Philadelphia Eagles]], [[Los Angeles Rams]], [[Houston Oilers]] and [[Buffalo Bills]]. Unlike the \"soccer style\" approach which was becoming more and more widely used during his career, Dempsey's kicking style was the then-standard straight-toe style.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mitchell|first=Fred|title=IT'S A GAME OF INCHES . . . AND FEET|date=December 24, 1995|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|publisher=[[Tribune Publishing]]|location=[[Chicago]]|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1995-09-24-9509240039-story.html|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDempsey was born in [[Milwaukee]] and attended high school and college in Southern California. He attended high school at [[San Dieguito High School]] and played [[college football]] at [[Palomar College]]. He was born with no toes on his right foot and no fingers on his right hand. Dempsey wore a custom, flat-front kicking shoe that ended where his toes were supposed to begin.<ref name=\"McLaughlin\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/05/us/tom-dempsey-nfl-kicker-dies-coronavirus-trnd/index.html|title=Tom Dempsey, NFL kicker who set a record for the longest field goal, dies of coronavirus|first=Eliott C.|last=McLaughlin|work=[[CNN]]|publisher=[[WarnerMedia]]|location=[[Atlanta]]|date=April 5, 2020|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==NFL career==\nDempsey is most widely known for kicking a 63-yard [[Field goal (football)|field goal]] as time expired to give the Saints a 19\u201317 win over the [[Detroit Lions]] on November 8, 1970 at [[Tulane Stadium]] in [[New Orleans]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Rovin|first=Jeff|title=In Search of Trivia|publisher=[[Penguin Books]]|location=[[New York City]]|year=1984|edition=1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/insearchoftrivia00jeff/page/408 408]|isbn=978-0451162502|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/insearchoftrivia00jeff/page/408}}</ref> Prior to 1974, the goal posts in the NFL were on the goal lines instead of the end lines.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tainier|first=Mike|title=Manadatory Monday: Snow Mess|date=December 9, 2013|work=Sports On Earth|publisher=MLB Advanced Media, L.P.|location=United States|url=http://www.sportsonearth.com/article/64493936/|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> With time running out in the game, the Saints attempted a field goal with holder [[Joe Scarpati]] spotting at the Saints' own 37-yard line. The snap from [[Jackie Burkett]] was good, and Dempsey made the field goal as the ball fell just beyond the bar.<ref name=culpepper_12102013>{{cite news|last=Culpepper|first=Chuck|title=Still The One|date=December 10, 2013|work=Sports on Earth|url=http://www.sportsonearth.com/article/64526706|publisher=MLB Advanced Media, L.P.|location=United States|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> The win was one of only two for the Saints in that dismal season.<ref name=vargas_04042020>{{cite news|last=Vargas|first=Ramon Antonio|title=Tom Dempsey, historic New Orleans Saints placekicker, dies at 73 after coronavirus battle|date=April 4, 2020|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune/The New Orleans Advocate]]|publisher=Georges Media Group|location=[[New Orleans]]|url=https://www.nola.com/sports/saints/article_f4822bdf-7ef3-522e-8634-54ad5805dc21.html|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> \n\nWith the kick, Dempsey broke [[Bert Rechichar]]'s NFL record for longest field goal by seven yards. His record was tied three times\u2014by [[Jason Elam]] in 1998, [[Sebastian Janikowski]] in 2011 and [[David Akers]] in 2012<ref>{{cite news|last=Lewis|first=Ted|title=Denver kicker breaks Tom Dempsey\u2019s record with 64-yard field goal|date=December 8, 2013|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune/The New Orleans Advocate]]|publisher=Georges Media Group|location=[[New Orleans]]|url=https://www.nola.com/sports/article_10db0910-6987-5319-a780-12bb2c94a5b8.html|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\u2014before it was broken on December 8, 2013,\nby [[Matt Prater]] who hit a 64-yard field goal.<ref name=vargas_04042020/>  Dempsey's kick along with [[Graham Gano]]'s 63-yarder in 2018 are the longest field goals to win a game on its final play.<ref name=culpepper_12102013/>\n\n[[File:Tom dempsey.jpg|thumb|left|Dempsey's special kicking shoe]]\nDempsey was born without toes on his right foot and no fingers on his right hand. He wore a modified shoe with a flattened and enlarged toe surface. This generated controversy about whether such a shoe gave a player an unfair advantage.<ref name=daye_12022014>{{cite news|last=Daye|first=Raymond L.|date=December 2, 2014|title=Remembering \"The Kick\"|location=[[Marksville, Louisiana]]|publisher=Avoyelles Publishing Company|url=http://avoyellestoday.com/index.php/sports/1750-remembering-the-kick|work=[[Avoyelles Journal]]|publisher=Avoyelles Journal, Bunkie, Record, Marksville Weekly |accessdate=January 4, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104052651/http://avoyellestoday.com/index.php/sports/1750-remembering-the-kick|archivedate=January 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/28/sports/playmagazine/28lewis.html?pagewanted=8|title=The Kick Is Up and It's...A Career-Killer|work=[[The New York Times]]|first=Michael|last=Lewis|date=October 28, 2007|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|location=[[New York City]]accessdate=May 25, 2010}}</ref> When reporters would ask him if he thought it was unfair, he said, \"Unfair, eh? How 'bout you try kickin' a 63 yard field goal to win it with 2 seconds left an' yer wearin' a square shoe, oh yeah, and no toes either.\"<ref name=daye_12022014/> Additionally, when an analysis of his kick was carried out by [[ESPN]] ''[[Sport Science (TV series)|Sport Science]]'', it was found that his modified shoe had offered him no advantage. In fact, it was found that the smaller contact area could have reduced, not increased, the margin for error.<ref>{{cite web|title=World's Longest Field Goal|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uu7IqQNA6Ls|publisher=ESPN Sport's Science}}</ref>\n\nThe league made two rule changes in the subsequent years to discourage further long field goal attempts. The first was in 1974, which moved the goal posts from the goal line to the back of the end zone, adding ten yards to the kick distance, and awarded the ball to the defense on a missed kick at the spot where the ball was snapped. This was changed in 1994 to the spot of the kick. Then, in 1977, the [[1977 NFL season#Major rule changes|NFL added a rule]], informally known as the \"Tom Dempsey Rule\", that \"any shoe that is worn by a player with an artificial limb on his kicking leg must have a kicking surface that conforms to that of a normal kicking shoe.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballresearch.com/articles/frpage.cfm?topic=rulesname|title=Rules of the Name, or How the Emmitt Rule Became the Emmitt Rule,|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071211145916/http://www.footballresearch.com/articles/frpage.cfm?topic=rulesname|work=[[Professional Football Researchers Association]]|location=[[Grand Island, New York]]|publisher=PFRA, LLC|archivedate=December 11, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogmedia.thenewstribune.com/media/2006%20NFL%20RULEBOOK.pdf|title=Official NFL Rulebook 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100216075609/http://blogmedia.thenewstribune.com/media/2006%20NFL%20RULEBOOK.pdf|work=[[The News Tribune]]|publisher=[[McClatchy]]|location=[[Tacoma, Washington]]|archivedate=February 16, 2010}}See Rule 5, Section 3, Article 3 Paragraph (g)</ref>\n\n==Career regular season statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: auto; text-align: right; font-size: 90%; width: 800px;\"\n''Career high/best '''bold'''''\n|-\n! style=\"background:#DCDCDC;\" colspan=\"17\"| Regular season statistics\n|- style=\"font-size:x-small;\"\n!Season||Team (record)||{{abbr|G|Games}}||{{abbr|FGM|Field goals made}}||{{abbr|FGA|Field goals attempted}}||{{abbr|%|Field goal success percentage}}||{{abbr|<20|Field goals under 20 yards}}||{{abbr|20-29|Field goals between 20 and 29 yards}}||{{abbr|30-39|Field goals between 30 and 39 yards}}||{{abbr|40-49|Field goals between 40 and 49 yards}}||{{abbr|50+|Field goals 50 yards or over}}||{{abbr|LNG|Longest successful field goal}}||{{abbr|BLK|Field goal attempts blocked}}||{{abbr|XPM|Extra points made}}||{{abbr|XPA|Extra points attempted}}||{{abbr|%|Extra point success percentage}}||{{abbr|PTS|Points}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[1969 NFL season|1969]] ||style=\"t