 | 4\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 4\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 30\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[1998\u201399 NHL season|1998\u201399]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | Washington Capitals\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | NHL\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 50\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 0\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 5\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 5\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 102\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | \u2014\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | \u2014\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | \u2014\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | \u2014\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | \u2014\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" \n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 1998\u201399\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[Colorado Avalanche]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | NHL\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 12\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 2\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 4\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 6\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 17\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 19\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 1\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 3\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 4\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 38\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\" | NHL totals\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 1407\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 323\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 697\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 1020\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 3565\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 186\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 42\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 76\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 118\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 729\n|}\n\n===Coaching career===\n\n====NHL====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! colspan=\"6\"|[[Regular season]] !! colspan=\"1\"|[[Post season]]\n|-\n! G !! W !! L !!OTL!! Pts !! Division rank !! Result\n|-\n![[Washington Capitals]]||[[2011-12 NHL season|2011-12]]\n|60||30||23||7||(92)||2nd in Southeast||Lost in Conference Semi-Finals\n|-\n|}\n\n====OHL====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; text-align:centre;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! colspan=\"7\"|[[Regular season]] !! colspan=\"1\"|[[Post season]]\n|-\n! G !! W !! L !! T !! OTL !! Pts !!Finish !! Result\n|-\n![[London Knights|LDN]]||[[2001\u201302 OHL season|2001\u201302]]\n|68||24||27||10||7||65||5th in West||Lost in second round\n|- \n!LDN||[[2002\u201303 OHL season|2002\u201303]]\n|68||31||27||7||3||72||2nd in Midwest||Lost in second round\n|- \n!LDN||[[2003\u201304 OHL season|2003\u201304]]\n|68||53||11||2||2||110||1st in Midwest||Lost in third round\n|- \n!LDN||[[2004\u201305 OHL season|2004\u201305]]\n|68||59||7||2||0||120||1st in Midwest||Won [[Memorial Cup]]\n|- \n!LDN||[[2005\u201306 OHL season|2005\u201306]]\n|68||49||15||-||4||102||1st in Midwest||Lost in OHL Finals\n|-\n!LDN||[[2006\u201307 OHL season|2006\u201307]]\n|68||50||14||-||4||104||1st in Midwest||Lost in third round\n|-\n!LDN||[[2007\u201308 OHL season|2007\u201308]]\n|68||38||24||-||6||82||2nd in Midwest||Lost in first round\n|-\n!LDN||[[2008\u201309 OHL season|2008\u201309]]\n|68||49||16||-||3||101||1st in Midwest||Lost in third round\n|-\n!LDN||[[2009\u201310 OHL season|2009\u201310]]\n|68||49||16||-||3||101||1st in Midwest||Lost in second round\n|-\n!LDN||[[2010\u201311 OHL season|2010\u201311]]\n|68||34||29||-||5||73||5th in Midwest||Lost in first round\n|-\n!LDN||[[2011\u201312 OHL season|2011\u201312]]\n|26||20||5||-||1||(99)||1st in Midwest||(left to take Capitals coaching job)\n|-\n!LDN||[[2012\u201313 OHL season|2012\u201313]]\n|68||50||13||-||5||105||1st in Midwest||Won [[J. Ross Robertson Cup]]\n|-\n!LDN||[[2013\u201314 OHL season|2013\u201314]]\n|68||49||14||-||5||103||3rd in Midwest||Lost in second round\n|-\n!LDN||[[2014\u201315 OHL season|2014\u201315]]\n|68||40||24||-||4||84||3rd in Midwest||Lost in second round\n|-\n!LDN||[[2015\u201316 OHL season|2015\u201316]]\n|68||51||14||-||3||105||2nd in Midwest||Won [[Memorial Cup]]\n|-\n!LDN||[[2016\u201317 OHL season|2016\u201317]]\n|68||46||15||-||7||99||3rd in Midwest||Lost in second round\n|-\n!LDN||[[2017\u201318 OHL season|2017\u201318]]\n|68||39||25||-||4||82||3rd in Midwest||Lost in first round\n|-\n!LDN||[[2018\u201319 OHL season|2018\u201319]]\n|68||46||15||-||7||99||1st in Midwest||Lost in second round\n|-\n!LDN||[[2019\u201320 OHL season|2019\u201320]]\n|62||45||15||-||2||92||1st in Midwest||Post-season cancelled\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total ||1244||822||326||21||75||1740||10 Division Titles ||2 Memorial Cups\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of NHL players with 1000 points]]\n*[[List of NHL players with 1000 games played]]\n*[[List of NHL players with 2000 career penalty minutes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{icehockeystats}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Kevin Hatcher]] | title = [[Washington Capitals#Team captains|Washington Capitals captain]] | years = [[1994\u201395 NHL season|1994]]\u2013[[1998\u201399 NHL season|1999]] | after = [[Adam Oates]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Lindsay Hofford]] | title = [[London Knights#Coaches|Head coach of the London Knights]] | years = [[2001\u201302 OHL season|2001]]\u2013[[2011\u201312 OHL season|2011]]| after = [[Mark Hunter (ice hockey)|Mark Hunter]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Bruce Boudreau]] | title = [[List of Washington Capitals head coaches|Head coach of the Washington Capitals]] | years = [[2011\u201312 NHL season|2011\u201312]]| after = [[Adam Oates]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Mark Hunter (ice hockey)|Mark Hunter]] | title = [[London Knights#Coaches|Head coach of the London Knights]] | years = [[2012\u201313 OHL season|2012]]\u2013present| after = incumbent}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Washington Capitals}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunter, Dale}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian ice hockey centres]]\n[[Category:Colorado Avalanche players]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Kitchener Rangers players]]\n[[Category:London Knights coaches]]\n[[Category:Memorial Cup winners]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League players with retired numbers]]\n[[Category:People from Lambton County]]\n[[Category:Quebec Nordiques draft picks]]\n[[Category:Quebec Nordiques players]]\n[[Category:Sudbury Wolves players]]\n[[Category:Washington Capitals captains]]\n[[Category:Washington Capitals coaches]]\n[[Category:Washington Capitals players]]\n[[Category:Canadian ice hockey coaches]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2011}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1960|07|31}}\n| birth_place = [[Petrolia, Ontario|Petrolia]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| position = [[Centre (ice hockey)|Centre]]\n| played_for = [[Quebec Nordiques]]<br>[[Washington Capitals]]<br>[[Colorado Avalanche]] \n| shoots = Left\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 10\n| weight_lb = 200 \n| draft = 41st overall\n| draft_year = 1979\n| draft_team = [[Quebec Nordiques]]\n| career_start = 1980\n| career_end = 1999\n}}\n'''Dale Robert Hunter''' (born July 31, 1960) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] former professional [[ice hockey]] player and the former [[head coach]] of the [[Washington Capitals]] of the [[National Hockey League]] and current co-owner, president, and [[head coach]] of the [[London Knights]] of the [[Ontario Hockey League]]. Hunter was born in [[Petrolia, Ontario]], but grew up in [[Oil Springs, Ontario]], and was one of three brothers, with [[Dave Hunter|Dave]] and [[Mark Hunter (ice hockey)|Mark]], to play in the NHL.\n\n==NHL career==\n\n===Quebec Nordiques===\nHe was selected 41st overall by the [[Quebec Nordiques]] in the [[1979 NHL Entry Draft]] and played seven seasons in Quebec.\n\nAccording to his former [[Quebec Nordiques]] coach [[Michel Bergeron (hockey coach)|Michel Bergeron]], even though Hunter was nicknamed the \"Nuisance\" on ice (''La Petite Peste'' in French), he was known to be \"humble\" in the dressing room and a sort of \"gentleman\", close to all the players. He was the \"perfect player\", always the first to arrive at practice and ready to do all his best for the team. Thanks to his charisma, Hunter was a fan favourite in both Quebec and Washington. His leaving Quebec was seen as an obvious \"mistake\" linked to the team's future decline.<ref>\"Les Nordiques, notre \u00e9quipe\", video documentary (French), Imavision, 1998 (see also DVD reed. 2006).</ref>\n\nHunter was traded to the [[Washington Capitals]] along with [[Clint Malarchuk]] in return for two players and a 1987 first-round draft pick the Nordiques then used to select [[Joe Sakic]].\n\n===Washington Capitals===\nIn the [[1993 Stanley Cup Playoffs#Washington vs. New York Islanders|1993 Patrick Division Semifinals]] between the Capitals and [[1992-93 New York Islanders season|New York Islanders]], Hunter led his team with seven postseason goals. That performance, however, was marred by an illegal and vicious check on Islanders' star [[Pierre Turgeon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1138705/index.htm|title=Dale Hunter|work=Sports Illustrated|date=December 6, 1993|last=Crothers|first=Time|accessdate=January 11, 2011}}</ref> This illegal check occurred after Turgeon had stolen an errant pass of Hunter's and subsequently scored.  As Turgeon was celebrating, Hunter came up from behind and checked an unsuspecting Turgeon into the boards. As a result of the incident, Hunter was suspended for the first 21 games of the [[1993-94 NHL season|1993-94 season]] as part of new commissioner [[Gary Bettman]]'s effort to crack down on violent play.\n\nHe broke the 1,000 points barrier (and is the NHL record holder for requiring the most games to do so by a forward, at 1,308, as well having the most penalty minutes when reaching that scoring milestone). He played in the [[1997 NHL All-Star Game|NHL All-Star game]] in 1997. He also served as team captain from 1994 to 1999.\n\nIN 1998 he led the fourth seeded Capitals to their first appearance in the Stanley Cup Finals, defeating the [[1997-98 Boston Bruins season|Boston Bruins]], [[1997-98 Ottawa Senators season|Ottawa Senators]], and [[1997-98 Buffalo Sabres season|Buffalo Sabres]]. In the [[1998 Stanley Cup Finals|finals]], the Capitals were swept by the defending Cup champions, the [[1997-98 Detroit Red Wings season|Detroit Red Wings]], with the first three games being decided by one goal.\n\n===Colorado Avalanche===\nHunter finished off his career with the [[Colorado Avalanche]], the successor to the Nordiques, and helped the team to reach the Western Conference finals, losing in seven games to the eventual Stanley Cup champion [[Dallas Stars]]. On that team, he often played on the same line as two other renowned [[pest (ice hockey)|pest]] role players -- [[Claude Lemieux]] and [[Theoren Fleury]].\n\n==Post-NHL==\n[[File:Washington Capitals retired numbers red.jpg|thumb|The Capitals retired Hunter's number in 2000.]]\nHunter's sweater number (#32) was retired by the Capitals on March 11, 2000. During the ceremony, the Capitals presented Hunter with one of the penalty boxes from the [[Capital Centre]] (the Capitals former home arena), symbolic of his exceptional amount of time served for penalties.\n\nIn 2000, Hunter and his brother, [[Mark Hunter (ice hockey)|Mark]]\u2014also a former NHL player\u2014teamed up with Dale's former teammate on the Nordiques, [[Basil McRae]], to buy the [[London Knights]] of the [[Ontario Hockey League]]. Dale became team president and head coach. He led the Knights to the [[2005 Memorial Cup|2005]] and [[2016 Memorial Cup]]. On January 1, 2006, the Hunter brothers were named to the 2006 Mayor's New Year's Honours List for Sports by the City of London, Ontario. Hunter's older brother [[Dave Hunter]] is also a former NHLer. His son [[Dylan Hunter]] is an assistant coach for the Knights and his other son Tucker also played for the London Knights before pursuing his education at the University of Western Ontario.\n\nOn November 28, 2011, Hunter resigned his position as head coach of the Knights to take the same position with the Washington Capitals, succeeding [[Bruce Boudreau]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://capitals.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=603491&navid=DL%7cWSH%7chome#|title=Capitals Name Dale Hunter Head Coach|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=November 28, 2011}}</ref> His brother Mark then took over as Knights coach. Hunter's defense oriented system caused some conflict with star [[Alexander Ovechkin]] but it helped the struggling Capitals make the playoffs, where they upset the defending Stanley Cup champions [[Boston Bruins]] in the first round before being eliminated by the [[New York Rangers]], both postseason series going to seven games. On May 14, 2012, Hunter announced he was not returning to coach the Capitals in the 2012-2013 season, choosing instead to return to the London Knights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2012/may/14/gm-hunter-wont-return-capitals-coach/%7cWSH%7chome# |title=Hunter won't return as Capitals coach |date=May 14, 2012 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nOn May 14, 2019, Hockey Canada named Hunter as the Head Coach for Canada\u2019s National Junior Team at the [[2020 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2020 IIHF World Junior Championship]].<ref>Canada\u2019s National Junior Team and Canada\u2019s National Men\u2019s Summer Under-18 Team at the 2020 IIHF World Junior Championship</ref>  Hunter guided the team to the gold medal with a dramatic come-from-behind victory over Russia in the final game.<ref>https://www.hockeycanada.ca/en-ca/team-canada/men/junior/2019-20/world-championship/stats/game-summary?gameid=2677</ref>\n\n==Accolades and controversy==\nLate in the deciding Game 6 of the [[1993 Stanley Cup Playoffs#Washington vs. New York Islanders|1993 Patrick Division Semifinals]] between the Capitals and [[New York Islanders]], [[Pierre Turgeon]] stole the puck from Hunter and scored, putting the game out of reach. Hunter, who was trailing Turgeon on the play, checked Turgeon well after the goal as he started to celebrate. Turgeon sustained a separated shoulder from the hit, causing him to miss all but Game 7 against the [[Pittsburgh Penguins]] in the second round, as well as most of the series against the [[Montreal Canadiens]] in the conference finals.  New [[NHL Commissioner]] [[Gary Bettman]], who had earlier promised to crack down on violence, suspended Hunter for the first 21 games of the [[1993\u201394 NHL season|1993\u201394 season]]\u2014at the time, the longest suspension in league history for an on-ice incident (in terms of games missed). Years later, Hunter admitted that he'd gone too far.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/20314-A-Trip-Through-Hockey-History-Remembering-the-Dale-Hunter-Cheapshot\n |title=A Trip Through Hockey History: Remembering the Dale Hunter Cheapshot\n |first=Eric|last=Kuzmiak\n |date=April 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\nWith amassing a staggering 3565 penalty minutes, Hunter currently has the second-most penalty minutes in NHL history, after [[Tiger Williams|Dave \"Tiger\" Williams]] (although Hunter played 1,407 games to Williams' 962). The Capitals retired his No.&nbsp;32 jersey. Hunter is the only NHL player ever to score over 1,000 points and rack up over 3,000 penalty minutes (1,020 points and 3,565 PIMs over 1,407 NHL games).\n\nHe scored in overtime for Quebec in Game 5 of their 1982 opening round best-of-five series vs. the [[1981-82 montreal canadiens season|Montreal Canadiens]], and in 1988 scoring against [[Ron Hextall]] on a breakaway in overtime for Washington in Game 7 of their opening round best-of-7 series vs. the [[1987-88 Philadelphia Flyers season|Philadelphia Flyers]], making Hunter the first player in NHL history to score two overtime series-clinching goals in the playoffs.\n\nIn July 2006, Hunter was arrested and charged with [[Driving under the influence|DUI]].<ref>{{cite web\n   |url=http://lfpress.ca/cgi-bin/publish.cgi?p=148299&x=articles&s=knights\n   |title=Knights coach charged with drunk driving\n   |first=April|last=Kemick \n   |date=August 20, 2006}}</ref> The charges were dropped when the presiding judge ruled that his rights under the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms were violated for unlawful detention and being denied his right to his lawyer.\n\nIn September 2005, Hunter was suspended by the Ontario Hockey League for four games after a player left the bench to initiate a fight in an exhibition game.\n\nOn January 20, 2006, Hunter was suspended for two games and his team was fined $5,000 for Hunter's off ice abuse of the officials. In May 2006, Hunter was fined $5,000 by the OHL for criticizing officials after the Knights were eliminated from the playoffs in four straight games. In September 2006, Hunter was suspended by the OHL for two games after forward Matt Davis left the bench to engage in a fight during a game; OHL rules state that there is an automatic suspension for both the player and the coach if a player leaves the bench to become involved in an altercation.\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Playing career===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" ID=\"Table3\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"5\" | [[Regular season|Regular&nbsp;season]]\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"5\" | [[Playoffs]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n![[Season (sports)|Season]]\n!Team\n!League\n!GP\n![[Goal (ice hockey)|G]]\n![[Assist (ice hockey)|A]]\n![[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]]\n![[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]]\n!GP\n!G\n!A\n!Pts\n!PIM\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[1977\u201378 OMJHL season|1977\u201378]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[Kitchener Rangers]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[OMJHL]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 68\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 22\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 42\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 64\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 115\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 9\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 1\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 0\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 1\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 32\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| ALIGN