LDN||[[2018\u201319 OHL season|2018\u201319]]\n|68||46||15||-||7||99||1st in Midwest||Lost in second round\n|-\n!LDN||[[2019\u201320 OHL season|2019\u201320]]\n|62||45||15||-||2||92||1st in Midwest||Post-season cancelled\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total ||1244||822||326||21||75||1740||10 Division Titles ||2 Memorial Cups\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of NHL players with 1000 points]]\n*[[List of NHL players with 1000 games played]]\n*[[List of NHL players with 2000 career penalty minutes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{icehockeystats}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Kevin Hatcher]] | title = [[Washington Capitals#Team captains|Washington Capitals captain]] | years = [[1994\u201395 NHL season|1994]]\u2013[[1998\u201399 NHL season|1999]] | after = [[Adam Oates]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Lindsay Hofford]] | title = [[London Knights#Coaches|Head coach of the London Knights]] | years = [[2001\u201302 OHL season|2001]]\u2013[[2011\u201312 OHL season|2011]]| after = [[Mark Hunter (ice hockey)|Mark Hunter]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Bruce Boudreau]] | title = [[List of Washington Capitals head coaches|Head coach of the Washington Capitals]] | years = [[2011\u201312 NHL season|2011\u201312]]| after = [[Adam Oates]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Mark Hunter (ice hockey)|Mark Hunter]] | title = [[London Knights#Coaches|Head coach of the London Knights]] | years = [[2012\u201313 OHL season|2012]]\u2013present| after = incumbent}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Washington Capitals}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunter, Dale}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian ice hockey centres]]\n[[Category:Colorado Avalanche players]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Kitchener Rangers players]]\n[[Category:London Knights coaches]]\n[[Category:Memorial Cup winners]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League players with retired numbers]]\n[[Category:People from Lambton County]]\n[[Category:Quebec Nordiques draft picks]]\n[[Category:Quebec Nordiques players]]\n[[Category:Sudbury Wolves players]]\n[[Category:Washington Capitals captains]]\n[[Category:Washington Capitals coaches]]\n[[Category:Washington Capitals players]]\n[[Category:Canadian ice hockey coaches]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toCapitol Center(link changed toCapital Centre (Landover, Maryland)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dale_Hunter"}
{"title_page": "Mahmoud Jibril", "text_new": "{{short description|Libyan politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|birth_name     = Mahmoud Jibril el-Warfally\n|name           = Mahmoud Jibril<br/><small>\u0645\u062d\u0645\u0648\u062f \u062c\u0628\u0631\u064a\u0644</small>\n|image          = Mahmoud Jibril - World Economic Forum Special Meeting on Economic Growth and Job Creation in the Arab World cropped GNC.png\n|caption        = Jibril at the [[World Economic Forum]] Special Meeting in Jordan 2011\n|office         = [[National Forces Alliance|Leader of the National Forces Alliance]]\n|term_start     = 14 March 2012\n|term_end       = 5 April 2020 \n|predecessor    = Position established\n|successor      = TBD\n|office1        = [[List of heads of government of Libya|Prime Minister of Libya]]\n|president1     = [[Mustafa Abdul Jalil]]\n|deputy1        = [[Ali Abd-al-Aziz al-Isawi]]<br/>[[Ali Tarhouni]]\n|term_start1    = 5 March 2011\n|term_end1      = 23 October 2011\n|predecessor1   = [[Baghdadi Mahmudi]]\n|successor1     = [[Ali Tarhouni]] <small>(Acting)</small>\n|office2        = [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Libya)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n|primeminister2 = [[Ali Tarhouni]] <small>(Acting)</small><br/>[[Abdurrahim El-Keib]]\n|term_start2    = 5 March 2011\n|term_end2      = 22 November 2011\n|predecessor2   = [[Abdul Ati al-Obeidi]]\n|successor2     = [[Ashour Bin Khayal]]\n|party          = [[National Forces Alliance]]\n|birth_date     = {{birth date|1952|5|28|df=y}}<ref>{{cite LAF|id=n 87944302}}</ref>\n|birth_place    = [[Benghazi]], [[Kingdom of Libya|Libya]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.pitt.edu/Jibril_Lecture_Oct_31 |title=Pitt Alumnus Mahmoud Jibril\u2014President of Libya\u2019s National Forces Alliance and Former Prime Minister of Libya\u2014to Present Distinguished Lecture on Campus Oct. 31 |publisher=University of Pittsburgh |date= |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/libya/8748682/Libya-Moussa-Koussa-tried-to-get-job-in-new-government.html |location=London |work=The Daily Telegraph |title=Libya: Moussa Koussa 'tried to get job in new government' |date=8 September 2011}}</ref>\n|death_date     = {{death date and age|2020|4|5|1952|5|28|df=y}}\n|death_place    = [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]]\n|death_cause    = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n|alma_mater     = [[Cairo University]]<br/>[[University of Pittsburgh]]\n|religion       = [[Sunni Islam]]\n}}\n'''Mahmoud Jibril el-Warfally'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/news/middleeastreports/s_731085.html |title=Libyan rebels look to Pitt grad for voice &#124; TribLIVE |publisher=Pittsburgh live |accessdate=7 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111225045546/http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/news/middleeastreports/s_731085.html |archivedate=25 December 2011 }}</ref> ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u0648\u062f \u062c\u0628\u0631\u064a\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0648\u0631\u0641\u0644\u064a}}), also transcribed ''Jabril'' or ''Jebril'' or ''Gebril'' (28 May 1952 \u2013 5 April 2020),<ref>{{cite web|author=Alwasat News |url=http://en.alwasat.ly/news/libya/279080 |title=Former Libyan PM Mahmoud Jibril has died from complications related to coronavirus |publisher=En.alwasat.ly |date= |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> was a [[Libya]]n politician who served as the interim [[Prime Minister of Libya]] for seven and a half months during the [[2011 Libyan Civil War|Libyan Civil War]], chairing the executive board of the [[National Transitional Council]] (NTC) from 5 March to 23 October 2011.<ref name=\"officialsite\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ntclibya.com/InnerPage.aspx?SSID=8&ParentID=3&LangID=1|title=The Executive Board of the National Transitional Council|publisher=National Transitional Council|accessdate=25 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727183717/http://www.ntclibya.com/InnerPage.aspx?SSID=8&ParentID=3&LangID=1|archivedate=27 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theatlanticwire.com/global/2011/03/libyan-rebels-name-mahmoud-jibril-prime-minister/36014/|work=The Atlantic|date=23 March 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011|title=Libyan Rebels Name Mahmoud Jibril Their Prime Minister|first=Uri|last=Friedman}}</ref> He also served as the Head of International Affairs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFLDE76E0W120110715|agency=Reuters|work=Reuters Africa|date=15 July 2011|accessdate=25 July 2011|title=Excerpts from Libya Contact Group Chair's Statement}}</ref> {{As of|2012|07}}, Jibril was the head of one of the largest political parties in Libya, [[National Forces Alliance]].<ref>Chris Stephen [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jul/10/muslim-brotherhood-expectations-libyan-election Muslim Brotherhood fell 'below expectations' in Libyan elections] The Guardian, 10 July 2012</ref>\n\nToward the end of the conflict, Jibril was increasingly referred to by foreign governments and in media as the interim prime minister of Libya rather than as the chairman of the executive board, the title used to describe him on the NTC's website, but it was unclear whether this was an official title or simply referred to his position as the provisional council's [[head of government]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2011/05/13/136281833/libyan-opposition-leader-the-revolution-is-led-by-new-breed-of-generations|newspaper=National Public Radio|date=13 May 2011|accessdate=21 July 2011|title=Libyan Opposition Leader: The Revolution Is Led By 'New Breed Of Generations'|first=Eyder|last=Peralta}}</ref> Jibril's government was recognized as the \"sole legitimate representative\" of Libya by the [[International recognition of the National Transitional Council|majority of UN states]] including [[France]], [[Turkey]], the [[United Kingdom]], the [[United States]], [[Iran]], and [[Qatar]].<ref name=recognitionfrance>{{cite news |title=Libyan opposition fights for recognition both at home and abroad |url=https://www.dw.com/en/libyan-opposition-fights-for-recognition-both-at-home-and-abroad/a-14952376 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Deutsche Welle |date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. recognition of new Libyan government raises tough legal questions |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/checkpoint-washington/post/us-recognition-of-new-libyan-government-raises-tough-legal-questions/2011/07/19/gIQAb9BdNI_blog.html |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=[[Washington Post]] |date=19 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nJibril graduated in Economics and Political Science from [[Cairo University]] in 1975,<ref name=NTC/> then earned a master's degree in political science in 1980 and a doctorate in political science in 1985, both from the [[University of Pittsburgh]].<ref>{{cite book| url=http://digital.library.pitt.edu/cgi-bin/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=pittcommence;idno=1985e49956;seq=0024|title=University of Pittsburgh Commencement, 1985|date=28 April 1985|publisher=University of Pittsburgh|location=Pittsburgh, PA|page=22|accessdate=7 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nJibril led the team which drafted and formed the Unified Arab Training manual.<ref>{{cite news |title=Profile: Mahmoud Jibril |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-18838990 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |agency=[[BBC News]] |date=18 July 2012 |quote=He also wrote several books and ran leadership training programmes in several Arab states.}}</ref> He was also responsible for organizing and administering the first two training conferences in the [[Arab world]] in the years 1987 and 1988.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mahmoud Jibril Prime Minister of Libya (2011); Leader of the National Forces Alliance of Libya, National Forces Alliance of Libya |url=https://www.weforum.org/people/mahmoud-jibril |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> He later took over the management and administration of many of the leadership training programs for senior management in Arab countries including [[Bahrain]], [[Egypt]], [[Jordan]], [[Kuwait]], [[Libya]], [[Morocco]], [[Saudi Arabia]], [[Tunisia]], and the [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref name=NTC>{{cite web|url=http://ntclibya.org/english/council-members/|title=Council members|publisher=Interim Transitional National Council website|accessdate=15 March 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5x0zNNNFG?url=http://ntclibya.org/english/council-members/|archivedate=7 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2007 to early 2011, he served in the [[Muammar Gaddafi|Gaddafi]] regime as head of the National Planning Council of Libya and of the National Economic Development Board of Libya (NEDB).<ref name=\"Wikileaks09TRIPOLI764\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20110507222014/http://46.4.48.8/cablegate/wire.php?id=09TRIPOLI386&search=jibril%20National%20Economic%20Development%20Board ''Wikileaks \u2013 09TRIPOLI386''], reviewed and hosted at ''[[Politiken]]''</ref> While there, he was a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 and close friend of [[Saif al-Islam Gaddafi]] and promoted [[privatization]] and [[Economic liberalization|liberalization]] policies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thepassionateattachment.com/2011/10/27/mahmoud-jibril-and-qaddafi%E2%80%99s-wealth-redistribution-project/|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130104222814/http://thepassionateattachment.com/2011/10/27/mahmoud-jibril-and-qaddafi%E2%80%99s-wealth-redistribution-project/|url-status=dead|archive-date=4 January 2013|title=Mahmoud Jibril and Qaddafi\u2019s Wealth Redistribution Project|publisher=The Passionate Attachment|accessdate=7 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"peacereporter240311\">Enrico Piovesana [http://it.peacereporter.net/articolo/27574/Il+possibile+successore+di+Gheddafi ''Il possibile successore di Gheddafi''], peacereporter, 24 March 2011</ref><ref>http://46.4.48.8/cablegate/wire.php?id=09TRIPOLI386&search=jibril%20National%20Economic%20Development%20Board{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===National Transitional Council===\nOn 23 March 2011, amidst the [[Libyan Civil War (2011)|Libyan Civil War]], the [[National Transitional Council]] officially formed a transitional government and Jibril was appointed to head it.<ref name=\"AJNoAirForce2303\">{{cite news|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2011/03/201132316258646677.html|title=Libyan air force 'no longer exists'|newspaper=Al Jazeera|date=23 March 2011|accessdate=23 March 2011}}</ref> Jibril led meetings and negotiations with [[France|French]] President [[Nicolas Sarkozy]], a meeting that resulted in France officially recognizing the National Transitional Council as the sole representative of the Libyan people.<ref name=recognitionfrance/> He also met with UK Foreign Secretary [[William Hague]] and then-[[United States|U.S.]] Ambassador to Libya [[Gene Cretz]], successfully persuading them to publicly back the NTC.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/story/2011/03/29/f-libya-jibril.html|newspaper=CBC News|date=29 March 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011|title=Mahmoud Jibril: the international face of Libya's rebels|first=Daniel|last=Schwartz}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his appointment as the NTC's head of government, Jibril was referred to by foreign officials as both as the interim prime minister<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bradsherman.house.gov/2011/05/12/Letter%20to%20the%20Libyan%20Interim%20PM%20May%202011.pdf|publisher=Office of Congressman Brad Sherman|date=12 May 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011|title=Letter to the Libyan Interim PM|first=Brad|last=Sherman|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110601215923/http://bradsherman.house.gov/2011/05/12/Letter%20to%20the%20Libyan%20Interim%20PM%20May%202011.pdf|archivedate=1 June 2011}}</ref> and the chairman of the Executive Board,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=MEMO/11/509&format=HTML&aged=0&language=EN&guiLanguage=en|newspaper=Europa|date=14 July 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011|title=Statement by Commissioner \u0160tefan F\u00fcle following his meeting with Dr Mahmoud Jibril, Chairman of the Executive Board of the Libyan Transitional National Council|first=\u0160tefan|last=F\u00fcle}}</ref> the title attributed to him by the NTC official website.<ref name=\"officialsite\"/> References to Jibril as the prime minister, including by news organisations,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-26/libyan-rebels-seek-aid-as-qaddafi-calls-on-muslim-clerics-to-incite-jihad.html|newspaper=Bloomberg L.P.|date=26 August 2011|accessdate=26 August 2011|title=Libyan Rebels Seek Aid as Qaddafi Invokes Jihad|first1=Vivian|last1=Salama|first2=Emre|last2=Peker}}</ref> foreign government ministries<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ambafrance-ie.org/spip.php?article1682|publisher=Embassy of France in Dublin|date=24 August 2011|accessdate=26 August 2011|title=President Sarkozy receives Mr Mahmoud Jibril, Prime Minister of the National Transitional Council of Libya at the Elys\u00e9e Palace}}</ref> and world leaders,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/2011/08/26/about-face-for-berlusconi-who-feted-qadhafi.html|work=Dawn|date=26 August 2011|accessdate=26 August 2011|title=About-face for Berlusconi, who feted Qadhafi}}</ref> have increased significantly after rebels [[2011 Battle of Tripoli|entered]] [[Tripoli]] in late August 2011.\n\nIn his capacity as the NTC's top diplomat, Jibril was also referred to as the council's foreign minister,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2011/05/201151322439609422.html|newspaper=Al Jazeera|date=14 May 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011|title=US stops short of recognising Libya rebels}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/NewsDetail.aspx?ID=18743&title=Top-diplomats-set-for-Libya-talks-in-Turkey|work=The News International|title=Top diplomats set for Libya talks in Turkey|date=14 July 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref> though this may have been a colloquial title. [[Qatar]]-based news organization [[Al Jazeera]] also called him \"the NTC's chief of staff\" on at least one occasion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2011/07/201176153213449975.html|work=Al Jazeera|date=6 July 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011|title=Rebels make gains in western Libya}}</ref>\n\nThe Executive Board was sacked ''en masse'' by decision of the NTC on 8 August over its sluggish response to the assassination of General [[Abdul Fatah Younis]], [[Benghazi]]'s top commander.<ref name=fired>{{cite news|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2011/08/20118819142699446.html|work=Al Jazeera|date=8 August 2011|accessdate=8 August 2011|title=Libyan opposition dissolves leadership board}}</ref> Jibril was asked to form a new board subject to the council's approval.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/newsflash/index.ssf/story/libya-rebels-dissolve-executive-committee/1d0caf6aac1a4de1af5c451b3a26116c|agency=OregonLive.com|title=Libya rebels dissolve executive committee|date=8 August 2011|accessdate=8 August 2011|newspaper=The Oregonian}}</ref> Though Jibril stayed on as the board's chairman, a spokesman for the NTC said he would be required to spend less time out of the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/09/world/africa/09libya.html?_r=1&src=tp|work=The New York Times|title=Libyan Rebels Dismiss Entire Cabinet|first=Kareem|last=Fahim|date=9 August 2011|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 August, amidst the [[Battle of Tripoli (2011)|Battle of Tripoli]], Jibril gave a televised speech urging revolutionary fighters against looting, [[revenge]] killing, abusing foreign nationals, and mistreating [[prisoner of war|prisoners of war]].<ref name=\"POWs\">{{cite news |title=The world is watching, don't seek vengeance, rebel leaders tell Libyans |url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/latest-news/the-world-is-watching-dont-seek-vengeance-rebel-leaders-tell-libyans/news-story/a0acb65bbd8391ee8edbd3f765eee26f |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=22 August 2011}}</ref> He also called for unity and asked that police and army units in [[Tripoli]] disavow Gaddafi but remain at their posts. Jibril declared, \"Today, all Libya's people are allowed to participate in the building of the future to build institutions with the aid of a constitution that does not differentiate between a man and a woman, sects or ethnicities. Libya is for everyone and will now be for everyone. Libya has the right to create an example that will be followed in the Arab region.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/breaking-news/the-world-is-watching-dont-seek-vengeance-rebel-leaders-tell-libyans/story-e6frf7jx-1226119619994|newspaper=Herald Sun|title=The world is watching, don't seek vengeance, rebel leaders tell Libyans|date=22 August 2011|accessdate=25 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn September, Jibril \"proposed 36 names for a new cabinet, including friends and relatives, and retained the prime minister and foreign minister slots for himself.\" He later retracted the proposal when NTC members objected, but an anonymous council official said it had \"left a bitter taste\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/libyans-wait-and-worry-as-government-delays-forming-cabinet/2011/09/27/gIQAtVcr2K_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|first=Greg|last=Jaffe|date=28 September 2011|title=Libyans wait, and worry, as government delays forming cabinet}}</ref>\n\n====Resignation====\nOn 3 October 2011, Jibril announced that he would resign from government once the country had been \"liberated\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2011/10/2011103124138235256.html|title=Jibril vows to quit after Libya 'liberation'|accessdate=25 January 2012|newspaper=Al Jazeera|date=4 October 2011}}</ref> He later specified this meant the capture of [[Sirte]] from loyalist holdouts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/story/2011/10/08/sirte-saturday.html|agency=CBC News|date=8 October 2011|accessdate=23 October 2011|newspaper=CBC News|title=Libyan forces say liberation of Sirte is near}}</ref> On 20 October 2011, Sirte was [[Battle of Sirte (2011)|captured]] and [[Muammar Gaddafi]] was killed. Keeping his promise to leave at the war's end, Jibril resigned three days later. He was succeeded by [[Abdurrahim El-Keib]] on 31 October.<ref>{{cite news |title=Libya's Prime Minister Abdurrahim al-Keib in profile |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-15552501 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=2 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===In the National Forces Alliance===\nIn 2012, Jibril became a member of the newly founded political union, the [[National Forces Alliance]]. On 14 March 2012, he was elected leader of the alliance. Jibril represented his party in the [[2012 Libyan General National Congress election|General National Congress election]].<ref name=elections2012>{{cite web |title=General National Congress Elections in Libya |url=http://aceproject.org/ero-en/misc/libya-final-report-general-national-congres |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the national elections of 7 September 2012, Jibril described his party as a supporter of [[democracy]] and also as an advocate of [[Sharia]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kirkpatrick |first1=David D. |title=Election Results in Libya Break an Islamist Wave |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/09/world/africa/libya-election-latest-results.html |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=8 July 2012}}</ref> The NFA won the largest number of seats in [[2012 Libyan General National Congress election|these elections]].<ref name=elections2012/> At the time, Jibril ran for a second term as prime minister. Jibril won the first round of voting, with 86 votes, significantly more than the 55 votes obtained by his primary opponent, [[Mustafa Abushagur]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya's Assembly Elects Mustafa Abu Shagur As Prime Minister |url=https://www.emouaten.com/english/Libya-s-assembly-elects-Mustafa-Abu-Shagur-as-Prime-Minister_a2244.html |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> However, in the second round of voting, Abushagur ultimately defeated Jibril.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gattis |first1=Paul |title=Former University of Alabama in Huntsville professor ousted as prime minister of Libya |url=https://www.al.com/breaking/2012/10/former_uah_professor_ousted_as.html |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Al.com |date=7 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nJibril suffered from [[cardiac arrest]] and was admitted to the Ganzouri Specialized Hospital in [[Cairo]], Egypt on 21 March 2020. Three days later, he tested positive for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1=|title=Former Libya Prime Minister Mahmoud Jibril dies from coronavirus |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/libya-prime-minister-mahmoud-jibril-dies-coronavirus-200405162834328.html |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=5 April 2020}}</ref> Jibril died on 5 April 2020 at the age of 67.<ref>{{cite news |last1=El-Tablawy |first1=Tarek |title=Former Libya Premier Jibril Dies in Cairo From Coronavirus |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-05/former-libya-premier-jibril-dies-in-cairo-from-coronavirus |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* el-Warfally, Mahmoud G., ''Imagery and Ideology in U.S. Policy Toward Libya, 1969\u20131982'', University of Pittsburgh Press (December 1988), {{ISBN|978-0-8229-3580-3}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|Mahmoud Jibril}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Baghdadi Mahmudi]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of heads of government of Libya|Prime Minister of Libya]]|years=2011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ali Tarhouni]]<br/><small>Acting</small>}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=Position established}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[National Forces Alliance]]|years=2012\u20132020}}\n{{s-vac}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{LibyaPMs}}\n{{National Transitional Council}}\n{{2011 Libyan civil war}}\n{{Arab Spring}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jibril, Mahmoud}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Cairo University alumni]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Libya]]\n[[Category:National Forces Alliance politicians]]\n[[Category:Libyan Sunni Muslims]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Transitional Council]]\n[[Category:People of the Libyan Civil War (2011)]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Libya]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh faculty]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Egypt]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Libyan politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|birth_name     = Mahmoud Jibril el-Warfally\n|name           = Mahmoud Jibril<br/><small>\u0645\u062d\u0645\u0648\u062f \u062c\u0628\u0631\u064a\u0644</small>\n|image          = Mahmoud Jibril - World Economic Forum Special Meeting on Economic Growth and Job Creation in the Arab World cropped GNC.png\n|caption        = Jibril at the [[World Economic Forum]] Special Meeting in Jordan 2011\n|office         = [[National Forces Alliance|Leader of the National Forces Alliance]]\n|term_start     = 14 March 2012\n|term_end       = 5 April 2020 \n|predecessor    = Position established\n|successor      = TBD\n|office1        = [[List of heads of government of Libya|Prime Minister of Libya]]\n|president1     = [[Mustafa Abdul Jalil]]\n|deputy1        = [[Ali Abd-al-Aziz al-Isawi]]<br/>[[Ali Tarhouni]]\n|term_start1    = 5 March 2011\n|term_end1      = 23 October 2011\n|predecessor1   = [[Baghdadi Mahmudi]]\n|successor1     = [[Ali Tarhouni]] <small>(Acting)</small>\n|office2        = [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Libya)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n|primeminister2 = [[Ali Tarhouni]] <small>(Acting)</small><br/>[[Abdurrahim El-Keib]]\n|term_start2    = 5 March 2011\n|term_end2      = 22 November 2011\n|predecessor2   = [[Abdul Ati al-Obeidi]]\n|successor2     = [[Ashour Bin Khayal]]\n|party          = [[National Forces Alliance]]\n|birth_date     = {{birth date|1952|5|28|df=y}}<ref>{{cite LAF|id=n 87944302}}</ref>\n|birth_place    = [[Benghazi]], [[Kingdom of Libya|Libya]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.pitt.edu/Jibril_Lecture_Oct_31 |title=Pitt Alumnus Mahmoud Jibril\u2014President of Libya\u2019s National Forces Alliance and Former Prime Minister of Libya\u2014to Present Distinguished Lecture on Campus Oct. 31 |publisher=University of Pittsburgh |date= |accessdate=2013-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/libya/8748682/Libya-Moussa-Koussa-tried-to-get-job-in-new-government.html |location=London |work=The Daily Telegraph |title=Libya: Moussa Koussa 'tried to get job in new government' |date=8 September 2011}}</ref>\n|death_date     = {{death date and age|2020|4|5|1952|5|28|df=y}}\n|death_place    = [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]]\n|death_cause    = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n|alma_mater     = [[Cairo University]]<br/>[[University of Pittsburgh]]\n|religion       = [[Sunni Islam]]\n}}\n'''Mahmoud Jibril el-Warfally'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/news/middleeastreports/s_731085.html |title=Libyan rebels look to Pitt grad for voice &#124; TribLIVE |publisher=Pittsburgh live |accessdate=2013-03-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111225045546/http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/news/middleeastreports/s_731085.html |archivedate=25 December 2011 }}</ref> ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u0648\u062f \u062c\u0628\u0631\u064a\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0648\u0631\u0641\u0644\u064a}}), also transcribed ''Jabril'' or ''Jebril'' or ''Gebril'' (28 May 1952 \u2013 5 April 2020),<ref>{{cite web|author=Alwasat News |url=http://en.alwasat.ly/news/libya/279080 |title=Former Libyan PM Mahmoud Jibril has died from complications related to coronavirus |publisher=En.alwasat.ly |date= |accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref> was a [[Libya]]n politician who served as the interim [[Prime Minister of Libya]] for seven and a half months during the [[2011 Libyan Civil War|Libyan Civil War]], chairing the executive board of the [[National Transitional Council]] (NTC) from 5 March to 23 October 2011.<ref name=\"officialsite\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ntclibya.com/InnerPage.aspx?SSID=8&ParentID=3&LangID=1|title=The Executive Board of the National Transitional Council|publisher=National Transitional Council|accessdate=25 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727183717/http://www.ntclibya.com/InnerPage.aspx?SSID=8&ParentID=3&LangID=1|archivedate=27 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theatlanticwire.com/global/2011/03/libyan-rebels-name-mahmoud-jibril-prime-minister/36014/|work=The Atlantic|date=23 March 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011|title=Libyan Rebels Name Mahmoud Jibril Their Prime Minister|first=Uri|last=Friedman}}</ref> He also served as the Head of International Affairs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFLDE76E0W120110715|agency=Reuters|work=Reuters Africa|date=15 July 2011|accessdate=25 July 2011|title=Excerpts from Libya Contact Group Chair's Statement}}</ref> {{As of|2012|07}}, Jibril was the head of one of the largest political parties in Libya, [[National Forces Alliance]].<ref>Chris Stephen [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jul/10/muslim-brotherhood-expectations-libyan-election Muslim Brotherhood fell 'below expectations' in Libyan elections] The Guardian, 10 July 2012</ref>\n\nToward the end of the conflict, Jibril was increasingly referred to by foreign governments and in media as the interim prime minister of Libya rather than as the chairman of the executive board, the title used to describe him on the NTC's website, but it was unclear whether this was an official title or simply referred to his position as the provisional council's [[head of government]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2011/05/13/136281833/libyan-opposition-leader-the-revolution-is-led-by-new-breed-of-generations|newspaper=National Public Radio|date=13 May 2011|accessdate=21 July 2011|title=Libyan Opposition Leader: The Revolution Is Led By 'New Breed Of Generations'|first=Eyder|last=Peralta}}</ref> Jibril's government was recognized as the \"sole legitimate representative\" of Libya by the [[International recognition of the National Transitional Council|majority of UN states]] including [[France]], [[Turkey]], the [[United Kingdom]], the [[United States]], [[Iran]], and [[Qatar]].<ref name=recognitionfrance>{{cite news |title=Libyan opposition fights for recognition both at home and abroad |url=https://www.dw.com/en/libyan-opposition-fights-for-recognition-both-at-home-and-abroad/a-14952376 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Deutsche Welle |date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. recognition of new Libyan government raises tough legal questions |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/checkpoint-washington/post/us-recognition-of-new-libyan-government-raises-tough-legal-questions/2011/07/19/gIQAb9BdNI_blog.html |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=[[Washington Post]] |date=19 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nJibril graduated in Economics and Political Science from [[Cairo University]] in 1975,<ref name=NTC/> then earned a master's degree in political science in 1980 and a doctorate in political science in 1985, both from the [[University of Pittsburgh]].<ref>{{cite book| url=http://digital.library.pitt.edu/cgi-bin/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=pittcommence;idno=1985e49956;seq=0024|title=University of Pittsburgh Commencement, 1985|date=28 April 1985|publisher=University of Pittsburgh|location=Pittsburgh, PA|page=22|accessdate=7 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nJibril led the team which drafted and formed the Unified Arab Training manual.<ref>{{cite news |title=Profile: Mahmoud Jibril |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-18838990 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |agency=[[BBC News]] |date=18 July 2012 |quote=He also wrote several books and ran leadership training programmes in several Arab states.}}</ref> He was also responsible for organizing and administering the first two training conferences in the [[Arab world]] in the years 1987 and 1988.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mahmoud Jibril Prime Minister of Libya (2011); Leader of the National Forces Alliance of Libya, National Forces Alliance of Libya |url=https://www.weforum.org/people/mahmoud-jibril |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> He later took over the management and administration of many of the leadership training programs for senior management in Arab countries including [[Bahrain]], [[Egypt]], [[Jordan]], [[Kuwait]], [[Libya]], [[Morocco]], [[Saudi Arabia]], [[Tunisia]], and the [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref name=NTC>{{cite web|url=http://ntclibya.org/english/council-members/|title=Council members|publisher=Interim Transitional National Council website|accessdate=15 March 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5x0zNNNFG?url=http://ntclibya.org/english/council-members/|archivedate=7 March 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2007 to early 2011, he served in the [[Muammar Gaddafi|Gaddafi]] regime as head of the National Planning Council of Libya and of the National Economic Development Board of Libya (NEDB).<ref name=\"Wikileaks09TRIPOLI764\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20110507222014/http://46.4.48.8/cablegate/wire.php?id=09TRIPOLI386&search=jibril%20National%20Economic%20Development%20Board ''Wikileaks \u2013 09TRIPOLI386''], reviewed and hosted at ''[[Politiken]]''</ref> While there, he was a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 and close friend of [[Saif al-Islam Gaddafi]] and promoted [[privatization]] and [[Economic liberalization|liberalization]] policies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thepassionateattachment.com/2011/10/27/mahmoud-jibril-and-qaddafi%E2%80%99s-wealth-redistribution-project/|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130104222814/http://thepassionateattachment.com/2011/10/27/mahmoud-jibril-and-qaddafi%E2%80%99s-wealth-redistribution-project/|url-status=dead|archive-date=4 January 2013|title=Mahmoud Jibril and Qaddafi\u2019s Wealth Redistribution Project|publisher=The Passionate Attachment|accessdate=7 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"peacereporter240311\">Enrico Piovesana [http://it.peacereporter.net/articolo/27574/Il+possibile+successore+di+Gheddafi ''Il possibile successore di Gheddafi''], peacereporter, 24 March 2011</ref><ref>http://46.4.48.8/cablegate/wire.php?id=09TRIPOLI386&search=jibril%20National%20Economic%20Development%20Board{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===National Transitional Council===\nOn 23 March 2011, amidst the [[Libyan Civil War (2011)|Libyan Civil War]], the [[National Transitional Council]] officially formed a transitional government and Jibril was appointed to head it.<ref name=\"AJNoAirForce2303\">{{cite news|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2011/03/201132316258646677.html|title=Libyan air force 'no longer exists'|newspaper=Al Jazeera|date=23 March 2011|accessdate=23 March 2011}}</ref> Jibril led meetings and negotiations with [[France|French]] President [[Nicolas Sarkozy]], a meeting that resulted in France officially recognizing the National Transitional Council as the sole representative of the Libyan people.<ref name=recognitionfrance/> He also met with UK Foreign Secretary [[William Hague]] and then-[[United States|U.S.]] Ambassador to Libya [[Gene Cretz]], successfully persuading them to publicly back the NTC.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/story/2011/03/29/f-libya-jibril.html|newspaper=CBC News|date=29 March 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011|title=Mahmoud Jibril: the international face of Libya's rebels|first=Daniel|last=Schwartz}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his appointment as the NTC's head of government, Jibril was referred to by foreign officials as both as the interim prime minister<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bradsherman.house.gov/2011/05/12/Letter%20to%20the%20Libyan%20Interim%20PM%20May%202011.pdf|publisher=Office of Congressman Brad Sherman|date=12 May 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011|title=Letter to the Libyan Interim PM|first=Brad|last=Sherman|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110601215923/http://bradsherman.house.gov/2011/05/12/Letter%20to%20the%20Libyan%20Interim%20PM%20May%202011.pdf|archivedate=1 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the chairman of the Executive Board,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=MEMO/11/509&format=HTML&aged=0&language=EN&guiLanguage=en|newspaper=Europa|date=14 July 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011|title=Statement by Commissioner \u0160tefan F\u00fcle following his meeting with Dr Mahmoud Jibril, Chairman of the Executive Board of the Libyan Transitional National Council|first=\u0160tefan|last=F\u00fcle}}</ref> the title attributed to him by the NTC official website.<ref name=\"officialsite\"/> References to Jibril as the prime minister, including by news organisations,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-26/libyan-rebels-seek-aid-as-qaddafi-calls-on-muslim-clerics-to-incite-jihad.html|newspaper=Bloomberg L.P.|date=26 August 2011|accessdate=26 August 2011|title=Libyan Rebels Seek Aid as Qaddafi Invokes Jihad|first1=Vivian|last1=Salama|first2=Emre|last2=Peker}}</ref> foreign government ministries<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ambafrance-ie.org/spip.php?article1682|publisher=Embassy of France in Dublin|date=24 August 2011|accessdate=26 August 2011|title=President Sarkozy receives Mr Mahmoud Jibril, Prime Minister of the National Transitional Council of Libya at the Elys\u00e9e Palace}}</ref> and world leaders,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/2011/08/26/about-face-for-berlusconi-who-feted-qadhafi.html|work=Dawn|date=26 August 2011|accessdate=26 August 2011|title=About-face for Berlusconi, who feted Qadhafi}}</ref> have increased significantly after rebels [[2011 Battle of Tripoli|entered]] [[Tripoli]] in late August 2011.\n\nIn his capacity as the NTC's top diplomat, Jibril was also referred to as the council's foreign minister,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2011/05/201151322439609422.html|newspaper=Al Jazeera|date=14 May 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011|title=US stops short of recognising Libya rebels}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/NewsDetail.aspx?ID=18743&title=Top-diplomats-set-for-Libya-talks-in-Turkey|work=The News International|title=Top diplomats set for Libya talks in Turkey|date=14 July 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref> though this may have been a colloquial title. [[Qatar]]-based news organization [[Al Jazeera]] also called him \"the NTC's chief of staff\" on at least one occasion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2011/07/201176153213449975.html|work=Al Jazeera|date=6 July 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011|title=Rebels make gains in western Libya}}</ref>\n\nThe Executive Board was sacked ''en masse'' by decision of the NTC on 8 August over its sluggish response to the assassination of General [[Abdul Fatah Younis]], [[Benghazi]]'s top commander.<ref name=fired>{{cite news|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2011/08/20118819142699446.html|work=Al Jazeera|date=8 August 2011|accessdate=8 August 2011|title=Libyan opposition dissolves leadership board}}</ref> Jibril was asked to form a new board subject to the council's approval.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/newsflash/index.ssf/story/libya-rebels-dissolve-executive-committee/1d0caf6aac1a4de1af5c451b3a26116c|agency=OregonLive.com|title=Libya rebels dissolve executive committee|date=8 August 2011|accessdate=8 August 2011|newspaper=The Oregonian}}</ref> Though Jibril stayed on as the board's chairman, a spokesman for the NTC said he would be required to spend less time out of the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/09/world/africa/09libya.html?_r=1&src=tp|work=The New York Times|title=Libyan Rebels Dismiss Entire Cabinet|first=Kareem|last=Fahim|date=9 August 2011|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 August, amidst the [[Battle of Tripoli (2011)|Battle of Tripoli]], Jibril gave a televised speech urging revolutionary fighters against looting, [[revenge]] killing, abusing foreign nationals, and mistreating [[prisoner of war|prisoners of war]].<ref name=\"POWs\">{{cite news |title=The world is watching, don't seek vengeance, rebel leaders tell Libyans |url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/latest-news/the-world-is-watching-dont-seek-vengeance-rebel-leaders-tell-libyans/news-story/a0acb65bbd8391ee8edbd3f765eee26f |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=22 August 2011}}</ref> He also called for unity and asked that police and army units in [[Tripoli]] disavow Gaddafi but remain at their posts. Jibril declared, \"Today, all Libya's people are allowed to participate in the building of the future to build institutions with the aid of a constitution that does not differentiate between a man and a woman, sects or ethnicities. Libya is for everyone and will now be for everyone. Libya has the right to create an example that will be followed in the Arab region.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/breaking-news/the-world-is-watching-dont-seek-vengeance-rebel-leaders-tell-libyans/story-e6frf7jx-1226119619994|newspaper=Herald Sun|title=The world is watching, don't seek vengeance, rebel leaders tell Libyans|date=22 August 2011|accessdate=25 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn September, Jibril \"proposed 36 names for a new cabinet, including friends and relatives, and retained the prime minister and foreign minister slots for himself.\" He later retracted the proposal when NTC members objected, but an anonymous council official said it had \"left a bitter taste\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/libyans-wait-and-worry-as-government-delays-forming-cabinet/2011/09/27/gIQAtVcr2K_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|first=Greg|last=Jaffe|date=28 September 2011|title=Libyans wait, and worry, as government delays forming cabinet}}</ref>\n\n====Resignation====\nOn 3 October 2011, Jibril announced that he would resign from government once the country had been \"liberated\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2011/10/2011103124138235256.html|title=Jibril vows to quit after Libya 'liberation'|accessdate=25 January 2012|newspaper=Al Jazeera|date=4 October 2011}}</ref> He later specified this meant the capture of [[Sirte]] from loyalist holdouts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/story/2011/10/08/sirte-saturday.html|agency=CBC News|date=8 October 2011|accessdate=23 October 2011|newspaper=CBC News|title=Libyan forces say liberation of Sirte is near}}</ref> On 20 October 2011, Sirte was [[Battle of Sirte (2011)|captured]] and [[Muammar Gaddafi]] was killed. Keeping his promise to leave at the war's end, Jibril resigned three days later. He was succeeded by [[Abdurrahim El-Keib]] on 31 October.<ref>{{cite news |title=Libya's Prime Minister Abdurrahim al-Keib in profile |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-15552501 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=2 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===In the National Forces Alliance===\nIn 2012, Jibril became a member of the newly founded political union, the [[National Forces Alliance]]. On 14 March 2012, he was elected leader of the alliance. Jibril represented his party in the [[2012 Libyan General National Congress election|General National Congress election]].<ref name=elections2012>{{cite web |title=General National Congress Elections in Libya |url=http://aceproject.org/ero-en/misc/libya-final-report-general-national-congres |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the national elections of September 7, 2012, Jibril described his party as a supporter of [[democracy]] and also as an advocate of [[Sharia]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kirkpatrick |first1=David D. |title=Election Results in Libya Break an Islamist Wave |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/09/world/africa/libya-election-latest-results.html |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=8 July 2012}}</ref> The NFA won the largest number of seats in [[2012 Libyan General National Congress election|these elections]].<ref name=elections2012/> At the time, Jibril ran for a second term as prime minister. Jibril won the first round of voting, with 86 votes, significantly more than the 55 votes obtained by his primary opponent, [[Mustafa Abushagur]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya's Assembly Elects Mustafa Abu Shagur As Prime Minister |url=https://www.emouaten.com/english/Libya-s-assembly-elects-Mustafa-Abu-Shagur-as-Prime-Minister_a2244.html |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> However, in the second round of voting, Abushagur ultimately defeated Jibril.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gattis |first1=Paul |title=Former University of Alabama in Huntsville professor ousted as prime minister of Libya |url=https://www.al.com/breaking/2012/10/former_uah_professor_ousted_as.html |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Al.com |date=7 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nJibril suffered from [[cardiac arrest]] and was admitted to the Ganzouri Specialized Hospital in [[Cairo]], Egypt on 21 March 2020. Three days later, he tested positive for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1=|title=Former Libya Prime Minister Mahmoud Jibril dies from coronavirus |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/libya-prime-minister-mahmoud-jibril-dies-coronavirus-200405162834328.html |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=5 April 2020}}</ref> Jibril died on 5 April 2020 at the age of 67.<ref>{{cite news |last1=El-Tablawy |first1=Tarek |title=Former Libya Premier Jibril Dies in Cairo From Coronavirus |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-05/former-libya-premier-jibril-dies-in-cairo-from-coronavirus |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* el-Warfally, Mahmoud G., ''Imagery and Ideology in U.S. Policy Toward Libya, 1969\u20131982'', University of Pittsburgh Press (December 1988), {{ISBN|978-0-8229-3580-3}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|Mahmoud Jibril}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Baghdadi Mahmudi]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of heads of government of Libya|Prime Minister of Libya]]|years=2011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ali Tarhouni]]<br/><small>Acting</small>}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=Position established}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[National Forces Alliance]]|years=2012\u20132020}}\n{{s-vac}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{LibyaPMs}}\n{{National Transitional Council}}\n{{2011 Libyan civil war}}\n{{Arab Spring}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jibril, Mahmoud}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Cairo University alumni]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Libya]]\n[[Category:National Forces Alliance politicians]]\n[[Category:Libyan Sunni Muslims]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Transitional Council]]\n[[Category:People of the Libyan Civil War (2011)]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Libya]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh faculty]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Egypt]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahmoud_Jibril"}
{"title_page": "Naci\u00f3n ESPN", "text_new": "{{Infobox television | show_name=Naci\u00f3n ESPN\n| runtime = 60 minutes (including commercials)\n| presenter = [[David Faitelson]]<br>Mauricio Pedroza<br>[[Pilar P\u00e9rez (TV host)|Pilar P\u00e9rez]]\n| language             = [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n| country = United States\n| network = [[ESPN Deportes]]\n| location = [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]]\n| first_aired          = February 14, 2011\n| last_aired           = December 21, 2018\n| related              = ''[[SportsNation (TV series)|SportsNation]]''\n}}\n'''''Naci\u00f3n ESPN'''''<ref>http://www.thestreet.com/story/10764173/1/espn-deportes-unveils-programming-initiatives-for-the-2010-2011-upfront-season.html</ref><ref>http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i6478fc41cf5464a509ac031cc8b9d6d9</ref> was a sports-related talk show, modeled after [[ESPN]]'s [[SportsNation (TV series)|Sportsnation]] TV series. It was hosted by three sports journalists in the Latino market, [[David Faitelson]], Mauricio Pedroza and [[Pilar P\u00e9rez (TV host)|Pilar P\u00e9rez]], who feature strong opinions, heated debates, celebrity interviews and heavy interaction with fans from all of the existing social media platforms.  The one-hour, Monday-thru-Friday show, is built around the fan and produced from the \u201c[[L.A. Live]]\u201d studios in [[High-definition television|HD]]. The show may establish [[Los Angeles]] as the Spanish language capital for ESPN.  It premiered on [[ESPN Deportes]] February 14, 2011. The show also began airing on ESPN for Mexico and Latin America since May 20, 2011.\n\nThe show was created by [[Ignacio Garcia (ESPN)|Ignacio Garcia]], Coordinating Producer in charge of all TV Productions for ESPN Deportes and ESPN International originated from Los Angeles. The show received the EMMY Award for Outstanding Sports TV Show in 2014. The same year, Garcia also expanded the brand with ''Naci\u00f3n ESPN Fin de Semana'', the weekend version that shows the Top 50 best and worst plays of the week.\n\nGarcia also launched the English-language version of the program airing on [[ESPN2]] on Monday, September 26. \nThe one-hour afternoon interactive sports talk show is targeting bilingual U.S. Hispanic sports fans.\n\u201cNaci\u00f3n ESPN\u201d on ESPN2 is hosted by three Latino commentators: [[Jorge Sedano]], co-host of ESPNLA\u2019s Mornings with Keyshawn and Jorge and LZ, [[Bernardo Osuna]], ESPN\u2019s bilingual boxing reporter and host of ESPN Deportes\u2019 A Los Golpes, and baseball expert [[Marly Rivera]].\nThe show airs live at 5 p.m. ET on Mondays from ESPN\u2019s studios in Los Angeles.\nThe show leverages the crossover that exists between the programs, connecting the ESPN and ESPN Deportes audiences.\n\nThe show ended its run on December 21, 2018 and was replaced by ''Ahora o Nunca'', a Spanish-language version of [[ESPN2]]'s ''Now or Never''.\n\n== Notable Segments ==\n\n===Ask the Professional===\nA celebrity has to answer five sports and general knowledge questions in 300 seconds. If the answer is correct the clock stops. If the answer is wrong 60 seconds are taken off the clock. The time left will show how much they know.\n\n===Did You Hear That?===\n\nSport-related sound bites of sports figures saying something humorous or outrageous.\n\n===Gotcha!===\n\nPlayers caught on tape with hidden cameras during a practical joke or a funny situation.\n\n===Weird Web Stories===\n\nUnusual and often not sports related videos from the Internet.  Last video will be paused in the middle so the co-hosts can guess what will happen next.\n\n===Montage of Soundbites===\n\nMontage of different sound bites from sports personalities pretending that are reacting to a specific topic.\n\n===The Skinny Lady and The Fat Man===\n\nTabloid-like TV entertainment news segment that will cover the glamorous side of athletes.\n\n===3 Cheers/Jeers/Tears===\n\nThe good, bad, and embarrassing  plays of the day.\n\n===The Best of ESPN===\nThe best and funniest moments from the different shows of ESPN International.\n\n== Fan Involvement ==\n\nSports fans will find '''''Naci\u00f3n ESPN''''' as the place to express their opinions and interact with the co-hosts thru online forums, poll questions, [[YouTube]], [[Twitter|Tweets]], [[SMS]] and even as part of a live audience in the studio  <ref>A show preview on YouTube gives fans a sneak peek of the show.</ref>\n\n===Fan Related Segments===\n*'''What would you do?''' Fans will say what would they do if they were in the shoes of a famous player or coach.\n*'''Pulse of the Nation''' Top 5 tweets of the day.\n*'''Who knows more?''' Camera asks people questions about current sports news and other topics in public areas showing the most outrageously, incorrect answers.\n*'''Pictures from fans'''  Fans displaying their crazy passion about sports and teams.\n*'''Funny videos from viewers'''  Fans displaying some sport ability or trick.\n\n== Celebrity guest appearances==\nEach night, a high-profile athlete, actor, singer, comedian or Latino public figure will be interviewed and involved in the different segments of the show.  The interview questions will focus on the interviewee's passion for sports, comical stories about their careers, and stories of the day in sports. \nShowing different sides of a celebrity's persona, the show will end each segment with some sort of a competition between the co-host(s) and the guest.  This activities will range from foosball competitions to basketball shootouts.\n\n===Focus on technology===\nThis show will be driven by the involvement of fans, the hosts, and technology, making it one of the most interactive and dynamic shows in television.  Thanks to the use of the latest technology available such us touch screen monitors, virtual graphics and web walls, the technology enhancement will provide a unique angle to the show, something totally unprecedented in Hispanic television.\nNaci\u00f3n ESPN will be the meeting place for sports entertainment and new technology on ESPN Deportes.\n\n==On-air staff==\n===Naci\u00f3n ESPN English-language version===\n*[[Jorge Sedano]] (2016\u20132018)\n*Marly Rivera (2016\u20132018)\n*Bernardo Osuna (2016\u20132018)\n\n===Naci\u00f3n ESPN Spanish-language version===\n*[[David Faitelson]] (2011\u20132018)\n*Rosy Martell (2015)\n*[[Adriana Monsalve]] (2011\u20132014)\n*Mauricio Pedroza (2015\u20132018)\n*[[Pilar P\u00e9rez (TV host)|Pilar P\u00e9rez]] (2016\u20132018)\n\n==See also==\n*[[SportsNation (TV series)]] - Original\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://sportsnation.espn.go.com/es/ Sports Nation]\n*[http://ESPNDeportes.com ESPNDeportes.com]\n*[http://ESPNLA.com ESPNLA.com]\n* [http://www.espnmediazone3.com/us/2010/05/espn-deportes-introduces-new-studio-show-from-los-angeles/]\n{{ESPN}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nacion ESPN}}\n[[Category:American sports television series]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language television programming in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television | show_name=Naci\u00f3n ESPN\n| runtime = 60 minutes (including commercials)\n| presenter = [[David Faitelson]]<br>Mauricio Pedroza<br>[[Pilar P\u00e9rez (TV host)|Pilar P\u00e9rez]]\n| language             = [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n| country = United States\n| network = [[ESPN Deportes]]\n| location = [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]]\n| first_aired          = February 14, 2011\n| last_aired           = December 21, 2018\n| related              = ''[[SportsNation (TV series)|SportsNation]]''\n}}\n'''''Naci\u00f3n ESPN'''''<ref>http://www.thestreet.com/story/10764173/1/espn-deportes-unveils-programming-initiatives-for-the-2010-2011-upfront-season.html</ref><ref>http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i6478fc41cf5464a509ac031cc8b9d6d9</ref> was a sports-related talk show, modeled after [[ESPN]]'s [[SportsNation (TV series)|Sportsnation]] TV series. It was hosted by three sports journalists in the Latino market, [[David Faitelson]], Mauricio Pedroza and [[Pilar P\u00e9rez (TV host)|Pilar P\u00e9rez]], who feature strong opinions, heated debates, celebrity interviews and heavy interaction with fans from all of the existing social media platforms.  The one-hour, Monday-thru-Friday show, is built around the fan and produced from the \u201c[[L.A. Live]]\u201d studios in [[High-definition television|HD]]. The show may establish [[Los Angeles]] as the Spanish language capital for ESPN.  It premiered on [[ESPN Deportes]] February 14, 2011. The show also began airing on ESPN for Mexico and Latin America since May 20, 2011.\n\nThe show was created by [[Ignacio Garcia (ESPN)|Ignacio Garcia]], Coordinating Producer in charge of all TV Productions for ESPN Deportes and ESPN International originated from Los Angeles. The show received the EMMY Award for Outstanding Sports TV Show in 2014. The same year, Garcia also expanded the brand with ''Naci\u00f3n ESPN Fin de Semana'', the weekend version that shows the Top 50 best and worst plays of the week.\n\nGarcia also launched the English-language version of the program airing on [[ESPN2]] on Monday, September 26. \nThe one-hour afternoon interactive sports talk show is targeting bilingual U.S. Hispanic sports fans.\n\u201cNaci\u00f3n ESPN\u201d on ESPN2 is hosted by three Latino commentators: [[Jorge Sedano]], co-host of ESPNLA\u2019s Mornings with Keyshawn and Jorge and LZ, [[Bernardo Osuna]], ESPN\u2019s bilingual boxing reporter and host of ESPN Deportes\u2019 A Los Golpes, and baseball expert [[Marly Rivera]].\nThe show airs live at 5 p.m. ET on Mondays from ESPN\u2019s studios in Los Angeles.\nThe show leverages the crossover that exists between the programs, connecting the ESPN and ESPN Deportes audiences.\n\nThe show ended its run on December 21, 2018 and was replaced by ''Ahora o Nunca'', a Spanish-language version of [[ESPN2]]'s ''Now or Never''.\n\n== Notable Segments ==\n\n===Ask the Professional===\nA celebrity has to answer five sports and general knowledge questions in 300 seconds. If the answer is correct the clock stops. If the answer is wrong 60 seconds are taken off the clock. The time left will show how much they know.\n\n===Did You Hear That?===\n\nSport-related sound bites of sports figures saying something humorous or outrageous.\n\n===Gotcha!===\n\nPlayers caught on tape with hidden cameras during a practical joke or a funny situation.\n\n===Weird Web Stories===\n\nUnusual and often not sports related videos from the Internet.  Last video will be paused in the middle so the co-hosts can guess what will happen next.\n\n===Montage of Soundbites===\n\nMontage of different sound bites from sports personalities pretending that are reacting to a specific topic.\n\n===The Skinny Lady and The Fat Man===\n\nTabloid-like TV entertainment news segment that will cover the glamorous side of athletes.\n\n===3 Cheers/Jeers/Tears===\n\nThe good, bad, and embarrassing  plays of the day.\n\n===The Best of ESPN===\nThe best and funniest moments from the different shows of ESPN International.\n\n== Fan Involvement ==\n\nSports fans will find '''''Naci\u00f3n ESPN''''' as the place to express their opinions and interact with the co-hosts thru online forums, poll questions, [[YouTube]], [[Twitter|Tweets]], [[SMS]] and even as part of a live audience in the studio  <ref>A show preview on YouTube gives fans a sneak peek of the show.</ref>\n\n===Fan Related Segments===\n*'''What would you do?''' Fans will say what would they do if they were in the shoes of a famous player or coach.\n*'''Pulse of the Nation''' Top 5 tweets of the day.\n*'''Who knows more?''' Camera asks people questions about current sports news and other topics in public areas showing the most outrageously, incorrect answers.\n*'''Pictures from fans'''  Fans displaying their crazy passion about sports and teams.\n*'''Funny videos from viewers'''  Fans displaying some sport ability or trick.\n\n== Celebrity guest appearances==\nEach night, a high-profile athlete, actor, singer, comedian or Latino public figure will be interviewed and involved in the different segments of the show.  The interview questions will focus on the interviewee's passion for sports, comical stories about their careers, and stories of the day in sports. \nShowing different sides of a celebrity's persona, the show will end each segment with some sort of a competition between the co-host(s) and the guest.  This activities will range from foosball competitions to basketball shootouts.\n\n===Focus on Technology===\nThis show will be driven by the involvement of fans, the hosts, and technology, making it one of the most interactive and dynamic shows in television.  Thanks to the use of the latest technology available such us touch screen monitors, virtual graphics and web walls, the technology enhancement will provide a unique angle to the show, something totally unprecedented in Hispanic television.\nNaci\u00f3n ESPN will be the meeting place for sports entertainment and new technology on ESPN Deportes.\n\n==On-air staff==\n===Naci\u00f3n ESPN English Language Version===\n*[[Jorge Sedano]] (2016\u20132018)\n*Marly Rivera (2016\u20132018)\n*Bernardo Osuna (2016\u20132018)\n\n===Naci\u00f3n ESPN Spanish Language Version===\n*[[David Faitelson]] (2011\u20132018)\n*Rosy Martell (2015)\n*[[Adriana Monsalve]] (2011\u20132014)\n*Mauricio Pedroza (2015\u20132018)\n*[[Pilar P\u00e9rez (TV host)|Pilar P\u00e9rez]] (2016\u20132018)\n\n==See also==\n*[[SportsNation (TV series)]] - Original\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://sportsnation.espn.go.com/es/ Sports Nation]\n*